1
00:00:30,440 --> 00:00:31,015
All right.

2
00:00:31,040 --> 00:00:32,686
Well, how else do we put up walls?

3
00:00:32,727 --> 00:00:34,729
We organize ourselves politically, right?

4
00:00:34,771 --> 00:00:36,655
And so we have hierarchies of social

5
00:00:36,680 --> 00:00:38,415
organization that surround us.

6
00:00:38,440 --> 00:00:41,156
And we've figured out how to formalize that so we

7
00:00:41,240 --> 00:00:44,135
can have conflicts and compete and cooperate

8
00:00:44,160 --> 00:00:46,495
without degenerating into absolute chaos.

9
00:00:46,995 --> 00:00:52,520
And then we also frame the world with our bodies.

10
00:00:52,918 --> 00:00:56,055
So part of the way that we solve the problem

11
00:00:56,080 --> 00:00:58,457
of the fact that we're surrounded by an infinite

12
00:00:58,499 --> 00:01:02,895
amount of that which we do not understand

13
00:01:02,920 --> 00:01:05,975
is that we can't see that much.

14
00:01:06,000 --> 00:01:09,320
You hear what you hear, but not everything.

15
00:01:09,508 --> 00:01:11,015
And you see what you see,

16
00:01:11,040 --> 00:01:13,094
but by no means everything.

17
00:01:13,178 --> 00:01:17,255
What you focus on visually is a very, very tiny

18
00:01:17,280 --> 00:01:20,080
percentage of what you could conceivably see.

19
00:01:20,105 --> 00:01:21,575
You don't see what's behind you.

20
00:01:21,600 --> 00:01:23,478
You don't see what's to the side of you.

21
00:01:23,520 --> 00:01:24,604
If I'm looking at you,

22
00:01:24,646 --> 00:01:26,022
I'm not looking at you, right?

23
00:01:26,063 --> 00:01:28,360
So even that focal perception restricts.

24
00:01:28,880 --> 00:01:33,120
Our bodies are—what did Huxley say?

25
00:01:35,071 --> 00:01:36,447
Who's the philosopher?

26
00:01:36,489 --> 00:01:38,240
I can't remember his name at the moment.

27
00:01:38,282 --> 00:01:40,075
Huxley wrote about this in The Doors

28
00:01:40,117 --> 00:01:42,975
of Perception, is that there's a world of infinite

29
00:01:43,000 --> 00:01:45,160
wonder around us all the time,

30
00:01:45,640 --> 00:01:48,535
but that infinite wonder is also overwhelming.

31
00:01:48,560 --> 00:01:51,600
And one of the things that being embodied does is

32
00:01:52,200 --> 00:01:55,855
restrict our view to the point where it's

33
00:01:55,880 --> 00:01:58,465
narrow enough so that we can master it.

34
00:01:59,160 --> 00:02:01,720
You don't see more than you can understand,

35
00:02:02,738 --> 00:02:03,160
perhaps.

36
00:02:03,880 --> 00:02:04,735
It restricts it.

37
00:02:04,760 --> 00:02:07,335
And so embodiment is another invisible frame.

38
00:02:07,360 --> 00:02:09,535
It excludes as much as it includes;

39
00:02:09,560 --> 00:02:11,040
it actually excludes more.

40
00:02:12,240 --> 00:02:13,686
And then

41
00:02:16,897 --> 00:02:22,986
there are sub-bodies, so to speak, within us.

42
00:02:23,880 --> 00:02:29,431
And you could think about those as instincts.

43
00:02:30,920 --> 00:02:32,327
Your senses frame the world.

44
00:02:32,369 --> 00:02:34,615
So you see the world visually, you hear the world,

45
00:02:34,640 --> 00:02:36,080
you touch the world, you taste

46
00:02:36,120 --> 00:02:37,500
the world, you smell the world.

47
00:02:37,525 --> 00:02:40,175
Those are avenues of encountering what you

48
00:02:40,200 --> 00:02:42,120
don't understand, so you can sample them.

49
00:02:43,520 --> 00:02:47,866
Your motivations and your emotions provide you

50
00:02:47,960 --> 00:02:50,895
with the basic structures of understanding

51
00:02:50,920 --> 00:02:53,160
that help you categorize the world.

52
00:02:53,680 --> 00:02:55,280
And they're there to begin with.

53
00:02:56,040 --> 00:02:58,760
So for example, if you say to your wife,

54
00:02:58,960 --> 00:03:00,800
"I'm hungry," she doesn't say,

55
00:03:01,040 --> 00:03:02,575
"What do you mean, hungry?"

56
00:03:02,600 --> 00:03:05,055
And the reason she doesn't say

57
00:03:05,080 --> 00:03:06,740
that is because she gets hungry, too.

58
00:03:06,800 --> 00:03:08,732
And so you can take that for granted.

59
00:03:08,774 --> 00:03:11,735
And the reason she gets hungry is because you

60
00:03:11,760 --> 00:03:14,640
have a biological system that operates within you.

61
00:03:14,960 --> 00:03:19,335
It's a subset of your body that regulates food

62
00:03:19,360 --> 00:03:22,520
intake and lets you know by craving

63
00:03:22,661 --> 00:03:24,245
when it is that you need to eat.

64
00:03:24,280 --> 00:03:26,655
And that's a universal experience.

65
00:03:26,680 --> 00:03:28,880
And it's one way that we parse

66
00:03:28,960 --> 00:03:31,200
the world apart instinctively.

67
00:03:31,760 --> 00:03:33,520
And so if you're hungry,

68
00:03:33,920 --> 00:03:36,040
your goal is to find something to eat.

69
00:03:36,088 --> 00:03:38,090
And so what happens when you're hungry,

70
00:03:38,120 --> 00:03:40,735
it isn't a drive that propels you

71
00:03:40,760 --> 00:03:42,677
deterministically through the world.

72
00:03:42,802 --> 00:03:45,080
What happens when you're hungry is that your

73
00:03:45,132 --> 00:03:47,259
hunger takes a grip of your vision,

74
00:03:48,040 --> 00:03:49,095
your internal vision.

75
00:03:49,120 --> 00:03:51,175
It says, "Your goal is now

76
00:03:51,200 --> 00:03:53,215
to find something to eat."

77
00:03:53,240 --> 00:03:55,960
And so now you're set up in a perceptual frame

78
00:03:56,280 --> 00:03:59,320
that orients the world in its entirety around the

79
00:03:59,800 --> 00:04:01,615
task that you're undertaking,

80
00:04:01,640 --> 00:04:03,200
which is to find food.

81
00:04:03,236 --> 00:04:04,821
And so the best way to think about

82
00:04:04,862 --> 00:04:08,240
hunger is as a personality or as a story.

83
00:04:08,947 --> 00:04:11,815
Hunger is the personality or the story that drives

84
00:04:11,840 --> 00:04:14,800
you into the realm of conceptualization

85
00:04:14,880 --> 00:04:16,120
that has food at its end.

86
00:04:16,400 --> 00:04:18,415
In the Exodus story, the Promised Land

87
00:04:18,440 --> 00:04:20,000
is the land of milk and honey.

88
00:04:20,120 --> 00:04:23,255
And that's partly because archaic people were

89
00:04:23,280 --> 00:04:25,975
hungry a lot, and milk is fat and honey is sugar.

90
00:04:26,000 --> 00:04:28,680
And when you don't have enough to eat,

91
00:04:30,120 --> 00:04:33,120
ice cream, that's sugar and fat, that's paradise.

92
00:04:33,480 --> 00:04:33,803
Right.

93
00:04:33,840 --> 00:04:36,520
And so when you're hungry, food is paradise.

94
00:04:36,880 --> 00:04:39,600
And so, and it sets up—it's not a drive.

95
00:04:40,320 --> 00:04:41,685
It's not a deterministic drive,

96
00:04:41,726 --> 00:04:42,811
because if you're hungry,

97
00:04:42,852 --> 00:04:44,604
you might have to solve extremely complex

98
00:04:44,646 --> 00:04:46,815
problems, like how to share food with other

99
00:04:46,840 --> 00:04:48,660
people, for example, in order to eat.

100
00:04:48,960 --> 00:04:52,657
So the hunger is a sophisticated subpersonality.

101
00:04:53,280 --> 00:04:57,280
And we have a variety of intrinsic,

102
00:04:58,000 --> 00:05:00,280
instinctual subpersonalities that we

103
00:05:00,400 --> 00:05:03,415
define as motivations that we all share.

104
00:05:03,453 --> 00:05:04,996
That's part of what makes us

105
00:05:05,913 --> 00:05:08,335
mutually comprehensible and fundamentally human.

106
00:05:08,360 --> 00:05:12,255
And so various physiologists have broken these

107
00:05:12,280 --> 00:05:14,571
motivational states down in various ways.

108
00:05:14,596 --> 00:05:16,920
But one reasonable rubric

109
00:05:17,560 --> 00:05:20,852
based on biological analysis is that you

110
00:05:20,960 --> 00:05:22,920
have two broad classes of motivation.

111
00:05:23,360 --> 00:05:25,935
One is designed to make sure

112
00:05:25,960 --> 00:05:27,480
that you continue to exist.

113
00:05:27,640 --> 00:05:30,895
Those are self-preservation motivations or

114
00:05:30,920 --> 00:05:33,720
self-maintenance, and the others are reproductive.

115
00:05:34,312 --> 00:05:36,814
And so, there's you, and you have to keep yourself

116
00:05:36,856 --> 00:05:38,899
going, but there's you in the social world, right?

117
00:05:38,941 --> 00:05:40,067
So you need a mate, and you

118
00:05:40,108 --> 00:05:41,443
to get along with other people.

119
00:05:41,485 --> 00:05:43,361
And there are different classes of motivation

120
00:05:43,400 --> 00:05:45,055
that serve those different needs.

121
00:05:45,080 --> 00:05:47,640
So in terms of self-maintenance,

122
00:05:48,282 --> 00:05:49,908
you get hot or you get cold.

123
00:05:49,950 --> 00:05:51,493
If you're taking care of an infant,

124
00:05:51,535 --> 00:05:52,702
you see this very clearly,

125
00:05:52,744 --> 00:05:54,486
because if your infant is distressed,

126
00:05:54,511 --> 00:05:56,747
it's usually because there's some basic

127
00:05:56,789 --> 00:05:58,698
motivational need that's not addressed.

128
00:05:58,723 --> 00:06:00,760
They're hot, they're cold, they're wet,

129
00:06:01,680 --> 00:06:03,335
they're thirsty, they're hungry,

130
00:06:03,360 --> 00:06:04,975
they're tired, right?

131
00:06:05,000 --> 00:06:07,000
Or they need to use the washroom.

132
00:06:07,548 --> 00:06:08,716
It's something like that.

133
00:06:08,757 --> 00:06:10,717
And so if you're taking care of an infant, you

134
00:06:10,759 --> 00:06:13,175
run through these different—is the baby too hot?

135
00:06:13,200 --> 00:06:14,595
Is the baby too cold?

136
00:06:14,637 --> 00:06:16,264
Does the baby need something to eat?

137
00:06:16,305 --> 00:06:17,264
Is the baby tired?

138
00:06:17,306 --> 00:06:19,455
And those are your basic initial solutions,

139
00:06:19,480 --> 00:06:24,479
and they suffice 95% of the time.

140
00:06:24,520 --> 00:06:25,935
And that's a good thing to know,

141
00:06:25,960 --> 00:06:26,981
if you have an infant.

142
00:06:27,023 --> 00:06:28,975
It's like, you go through the checklist.

143
00:06:29,000 --> 00:06:30,942
Even with little kids, it's the same thing.

144
00:06:30,984 --> 00:06:32,402
If they start to misbehave,

145
00:06:32,440 --> 00:06:35,520
they're often hungry—adults for that matter, too.

146
00:06:35,780 --> 00:06:38,135
I noticed when we had little kids that we'd take

147
00:06:38,160 --> 00:06:39,533
them out to a social event,

148
00:06:39,575 --> 00:06:41,785
and after like an hour, they'd start to misbehave,

149
00:06:41,827 --> 00:06:43,244
and then we'd leave, and my wife

150
00:06:43,286 --> 00:06:46,215
and I would think, "It was time to go."

151
00:06:46,240 --> 00:06:48,624
And the kids figured that out before we did.

152
00:06:48,690 --> 00:06:50,575
It's like, the adults will get crabby

153
00:06:50,600 --> 00:06:52,880
15 minutes after the kids get crabby.

154
00:06:53,080 --> 00:06:55,375
So anyways, you have these basic in-built

155
00:06:55,400 --> 00:06:57,655
motivations, and they're there at the beginning.

156
00:06:57,680 --> 00:07:00,080
And a two-year-old, for example, is really

157
00:07:00,105 --> 00:07:02,093
nothing but a bundle of those motivations.

158
00:07:02,120 --> 00:07:04,137
And one of the things that makes

159
00:07:04,320 --> 00:07:06,855
kids delightful is they just bounce through those

160
00:07:06,880 --> 00:07:09,440
motivational states, and they sort of appear.

161
00:07:10,240 --> 00:07:11,600
If a kid's angry,

162
00:07:12,310 --> 00:07:14,720
some kids in particular, they'll have a tantrum.

163
00:07:14,920 --> 00:07:17,320
It's like, they're just 100% rage.

164
00:07:17,600 --> 00:07:19,935
I've seen 30-year-olds have tantrums.

165
00:07:19,960 --> 00:07:21,655
I tell you, man, you want to call

166
00:07:21,680 --> 00:07:23,153
the police when that happens.

167
00:07:23,194 --> 00:07:25,400
It's really terrifying because a two-year-old

168
00:07:25,446 --> 00:07:26,739
who's having a tantrum is

169
00:07:26,781 --> 00:07:28,282
completely out of control.

170
00:07:28,320 --> 00:07:29,533
But they're, like, two.

171
00:07:29,760 --> 00:07:31,255
So what are they going to do?

172
00:07:31,280 --> 00:07:33,161
They're only this tall and you can just push

173
00:07:33,200 --> 00:07:35,079
them over if they cause too much trouble.

174
00:07:35,120 --> 00:07:38,375
But if you're 30 and you have a tantrum,

175
00:07:38,400 --> 00:07:40,960
oh my god, it's quite the terrifying display.

176
00:07:41,409 --> 00:07:44,579
And so, a two-year-old will cry and be enraged

177
00:07:44,720 --> 00:07:47,480
and be hungry and then be so happy

178
00:07:47,506 --> 00:07:49,175
that you can hardly even stand it.

179
00:07:49,200 --> 00:07:49,967
Neither can they.

180
00:07:50,008 --> 00:07:51,134
And they just cycle through

181
00:07:51,176 --> 00:07:52,375
these motivational states.

182
00:07:52,400 --> 00:07:54,560
And there's a real purity in that and a real

183
00:07:54,714 --> 00:07:57,133
intensity that makes being around them fun.

184
00:07:57,181 --> 00:07:59,175
But they can't take care of themselves,

185
00:07:59,200 --> 00:08:01,560
and they're nothing but a handful of problems.

186
00:08:01,600 --> 00:08:04,455
And if you have someone who's adult

187
00:08:04,480 --> 00:08:07,000
who's like that, like, god help you.

188
00:08:07,400 --> 00:08:09,295
So it's just fine when you're two,

189
00:08:09,320 --> 00:08:11,610
but when you're 30, it's getting a little old.

190
00:08:11,800 --> 00:08:15,080
One of the things that happens as a child matures,

191
00:08:15,160 --> 00:08:17,760
they have these in-built instinctive systems,

192
00:08:18,080 --> 00:08:20,560
and you might say, well, maybe that's good enough.

193
00:08:20,880 --> 00:08:24,080
And it's not, because the systems really

194
00:08:25,080 --> 00:08:26,160
present problems,

195
00:08:26,872 --> 00:08:29,455
but they're not that good at offering solutions.

196
00:08:29,480 --> 00:08:30,720
So when you're hungry,

197
00:08:31,360 --> 00:08:32,940
that's not the same as eating.

198
00:08:33,560 --> 00:08:34,520
It's the problem.

199
00:08:34,920 --> 00:08:36,339
The eating is the solution.

200
00:08:36,380 --> 00:08:37,465
The hunger is the problem.

201
00:08:37,506 --> 00:08:39,216
When you're thirsty, it's the same thing.

202
00:08:39,258 --> 00:08:41,093
These in-built motivational systems

203
00:08:41,120 --> 00:08:43,640
don't tell you how to solve the problem.

204
00:08:43,847 --> 00:08:45,815
And sometimes the problem is

205
00:08:45,840 --> 00:08:47,320
that the motivations conflict.

206
00:08:47,720 --> 00:08:49,016
You see this sometimes.

207
00:08:49,058 --> 00:08:50,309
Like, are you too hungry

208
00:08:50,350 --> 00:08:52,602
to sleep or too tired to eat?

209
00:08:52,840 --> 00:08:54,655
And you can see that you can have

210
00:08:54,680 --> 00:08:56,314
motivational problems of your own.

211
00:08:56,355 --> 00:08:57,982
Maybe you hate someone, but you're

212
00:08:58,023 --> 00:08:59,733
terribly sexually attracted to them.

213
00:08:59,775 --> 00:09:01,380
So that's another place where

214
00:09:01,405 --> 00:09:03,840
motivational systems will conflict.

215
00:09:04,160 --> 00:09:08,255
And so what happens as you mature is that those

216
00:09:08,280 --> 00:09:10,880
motivational systems have to be integrated so

217
00:09:11,520 --> 00:09:12,920
that they can be

218
00:09:14,120 --> 00:09:16,960
satisfied over a long period of time,

219
00:09:17,600 --> 00:09:20,855
so they can be satisfied in relationship to each

220
00:09:20,880 --> 00:09:23,640
other, and so they can be satisfied

221
00:09:23,920 --> 00:09:26,005
in the presence of other people.

222
00:09:26,200 --> 00:09:28,520
So maybe, you can see that with kids.

223
00:09:28,600 --> 00:09:31,480
So what are the elementary forms of socialization?

224
00:09:32,240 --> 00:09:35,615
Toilet training, because now there are lots of

225
00:09:35,640 --> 00:09:38,098
kids who are in grade 1 who aren't toilet-trained.

226
00:09:38,200 --> 00:09:40,360
That's become a real problem in places like

227
00:09:40,440 --> 00:09:42,975
the UK, is that we've allowed our families to get

228
00:09:43,000 --> 00:09:44,937
so fragmented that there are six-year-old

229
00:09:44,979 --> 00:09:47,200
kids who haven't been toilet-trained.

230
00:09:47,523 --> 00:09:48,274
Stunning.

231
00:09:48,411 --> 00:09:50,720
And you can see that if you haven't got that

232
00:09:51,240 --> 00:09:54,880
figured out by the time you're four,

233
00:09:55,680 --> 00:09:57,400
and that's really pushing it,

234
00:09:57,880 --> 00:10:00,220
that's going to cause a lot of social problems,

235
00:10:00,245 --> 00:10:01,451
to say the least.

236
00:10:01,493 --> 00:10:03,244
You're just not getting anywhere in life

237
00:10:03,286 --> 00:10:04,912
if you haven't got that under control.

238
00:10:04,960 --> 00:10:07,600
And so you see that that's a place where

239
00:10:09,680 --> 00:10:12,644
a basic biological motivation has to be integrated

240
00:10:12,669 --> 00:10:14,600
into a pattern of behavior that's socially

241
00:10:14,625 --> 00:10:15,796
acceptable,

242
00:10:15,960 --> 00:10:18,455
so that other things that are socially acceptable,

243
00:10:18,480 --> 00:10:20,050
other solutions that are socially

244
00:10:20,092 --> 00:10:21,569
acceptable, can be implemented.

245
00:10:21,600 --> 00:10:23,335
And that's what you're trying to do

246
00:10:23,360 --> 00:10:24,387
with your children.

247
00:10:24,429 --> 00:10:26,295
This is a good thing to know because

248
00:10:26,320 --> 00:10:27,440
the Freudian model,

249
00:10:28,535 --> 00:10:30,480
which is interesting but wrong, is

250
00:10:31,000 --> 00:10:32,415
the human being—well, it is,

251
00:10:32,440 --> 00:10:34,695
but interestingly wrong is useful, right?

252
00:10:34,720 --> 00:10:36,320
And it is interestingly wrong.

253
00:10:36,760 --> 00:10:39,440
So Freud conceptualized us in part as an id,

254
00:10:39,800 --> 00:10:42,880
which was a, what would you call, gathering place

255
00:10:43,480 --> 00:10:46,135
of instincts, mostly sexual for Freud,

256
00:10:46,160 --> 00:10:49,440
but instinct, instinctual compulsion and drive.

257
00:10:49,840 --> 00:10:51,615
And that would meet the superego,

258
00:10:51,640 --> 00:10:56,437
which was basically the social, patriarchal social

259
00:10:57,021 --> 00:10:59,720
community, potentially internalized, that says no.

260
00:11:00,480 --> 00:11:01,620
It's inhibition.

261
00:11:01,800 --> 00:11:04,279
It's like a Rousseauian model, in some sense,

262
00:11:05,040 --> 00:11:07,006
with a bit more negativity added.

263
00:11:07,040 --> 00:11:08,240
You're a mass of impulses.

264
00:11:08,265 --> 00:11:10,440
The impulses have to be met with control.

265
00:11:11,040 --> 00:11:13,280
OK, but that brings us to the force problem.

266
00:11:13,970 --> 00:11:15,888
It's like, is it control that you're

267
00:11:15,920 --> 00:11:17,807
trying to institute on your children?

268
00:11:17,834 --> 00:11:19,095
The problem with that is,

269
00:11:19,120 --> 00:11:20,575
if you use force and control,

270
00:11:20,600 --> 00:11:21,900
they're going to rebel,

271
00:11:22,080 --> 00:11:24,375
or you're going to intimidate them, or you're

272
00:11:24,400 --> 00:11:27,200
going to, or you're going to, what would you call?

273
00:11:27,840 --> 00:11:31,335
You're going to make them into resentful followers

274
00:11:31,360 --> 00:11:33,895
of stupid rules they don't understand,

275
00:11:33,920 --> 00:11:35,655
which is also not a good outcome.

276
00:11:35,680 --> 00:11:37,281
You can do that to yourself, too,

277
00:11:37,323 --> 00:11:39,880
by forcing yourself to do things that

278
00:11:40,320 --> 00:11:42,327
you're actually not inclined to do.

279
00:11:42,369 --> 00:11:43,786
It's complicated because you

280
00:11:43,828 --> 00:11:45,121
want to discipline yourself.

281
00:11:45,163 --> 00:11:46,160
So what are you doing?

282
00:11:46,205 --> 00:11:48,290
Well, you're offering the child a better game.

283
00:11:48,332 --> 00:11:51,280
As I said before, my son, when he was little,

284
00:11:51,305 --> 00:11:53,040
he was a pretty aggressive little kid.

285
00:11:53,065 --> 00:11:54,415
He had a good temper, and

286
00:11:54,440 --> 00:11:55,546
I liked playing with him.

287
00:11:55,588 --> 00:11:57,506
But now and then he'd get out of hand and get

288
00:11:57,548 --> 00:11:59,591
stubborn, and I'd go have him sit on the steps.

289
00:11:59,633 --> 00:12:01,259
And it was so interesting watching him,

290
00:12:01,301 --> 00:12:02,052
because, maybe,

291
00:12:02,093 --> 00:12:04,220
it probably happened from the time he was about 12

292
00:12:04,262 --> 00:12:06,722
months till he was about two, something like that.

293
00:12:06,758 --> 00:12:09,240
He'd sit on the steps because he, I don't know,

294
00:12:09,520 --> 00:12:11,055
he was enraged about something

295
00:12:11,080 --> 00:12:12,310
that didn't go his way.

296
00:12:12,805 --> 00:12:16,120
And the rule was, sit on the steps until you

297
00:12:16,720 --> 00:12:19,896
can play again, until you can act like a civilized

298
00:12:19,942 --> 00:12:21,320
human being that other people

299
00:12:21,345 --> 00:12:22,615
would like to have around.

300
00:12:22,640 --> 00:12:24,195
And so as soon as he would do that,

301
00:12:24,237 --> 00:12:25,415
he could get off the steps.

302
00:12:25,440 --> 00:12:27,281
It was so interesting watching him do that,

303
00:12:27,323 --> 00:12:28,616
because he'd sit on the steps

304
00:12:28,657 --> 00:12:30,895
with his fists clenched, his teeth clenched,

305
00:12:30,920 --> 00:12:33,840
and I'd go tap and say, "Are

306
00:12:34,329 --> 00:12:36,135
you ready to get off the steps?"

307
00:12:36,160 --> 00:12:37,706
"Not yet."

308
00:12:38,831 --> 00:12:41,280
But you could see, so what was happening is,

309
00:12:41,376 --> 00:12:44,895
he was trying to integrate those powerful forces

310
00:12:44,920 --> 00:12:48,335
of rage into a personality that would

311
00:12:48,360 --> 00:12:50,800
enable him to maintain his social relations.

312
00:12:51,320 --> 00:12:52,010
Now, look.

313
00:12:52,240 --> 00:12:54,095
If you can imagine this as an adult,

314
00:12:54,120 --> 00:12:56,175
is maybe you're having a difficult conversation

315
00:12:56,200 --> 00:12:56,847
with your wife,

316
00:12:56,889 --> 00:12:58,821
and she's afraid to do that because you have

317
00:12:58,849 --> 00:12:59,391
a temper,

318
00:12:59,416 --> 00:13:01,601
which means that you're not well socialized.

319
00:13:01,643 --> 00:13:03,394
She'll say something provocative,

320
00:13:03,840 --> 00:13:06,495
maybe that's just related to an actual problem,

321
00:13:06,522 --> 00:13:08,607
or maybe she's given you a poke just to find out

322
00:13:08,649 --> 00:13:10,275
what kind of son of a bitch you are,

323
00:13:10,320 --> 00:13:12,240
and you can't control your anger.

324
00:13:12,777 --> 00:13:14,112
And so what does that mean?

325
00:13:14,153 --> 00:13:18,415
It means that you haven't mastered the capacity

326
00:13:18,440 --> 00:13:20,840
to integrate the full range of your aggression

327
00:13:21,280 --> 00:13:23,080
into a sophisticated personality.

328
00:13:23,720 --> 00:13:25,760
That makes you dangerous.

329
00:13:25,880 --> 00:13:29,935
Part of the reason you see that in a developing

330
00:13:29,960 --> 00:13:32,175
relationship, for example, between a man and a

331
00:13:32,200 --> 00:13:34,480
woman, both partners will test each other out.

332
00:13:34,960 --> 00:13:37,548
And women will say provocative things to men.

333
00:13:37,590 --> 00:13:39,925
And men think, "Why the hell is that going on?"

334
00:13:39,967 --> 00:13:41,843
And the answer is something like,

335
00:13:41,880 --> 00:13:43,511
well, the women want to find out,

336
00:13:43,678 --> 00:13:46,055
if you're annoyed, if you turn into a murderous

337
00:13:46,097 --> 00:13:49,615
tyrant, because if you do, you're probably

338
00:13:49,640 --> 00:13:52,269
not the best person to have around children.

339
00:13:52,680 --> 00:13:55,615
And that's a really crucial thing to discover.

340
00:13:55,640 --> 00:13:57,015
And so you don't discover

341
00:13:57,040 --> 00:13:58,399
that just by asking someone.

342
00:13:58,440 --> 00:14:00,067
You have to poke them a bunch and see.

343
00:14:00,108 --> 00:14:02,373
It's like, can I elicit

344
00:14:02,457 --> 00:14:04,440
something in you that's untoward?

345
00:14:05,000 --> 00:14:06,480
And that's a deadly game.

346
00:14:07,003 --> 00:14:09,158
And it's not even necessary that the people

347
00:14:09,199 --> 00:14:10,992
who are playing it even know they are,

348
00:14:11,034 --> 00:14:13,119
but people will definitely play games like that,

349
00:14:13,160 --> 00:14:15,538
and they need to because you need to know.

350
00:14:15,760 --> 00:14:18,360
And it isn't that you control your temper.

351
00:14:18,415 --> 00:14:20,000
There are times when you have to,

352
00:14:20,042 --> 00:14:21,084
but that's not right.

353
00:14:21,126 --> 00:14:22,585
My son,

354
00:14:23,280 --> 00:14:25,855
who learned to integrate the part of him that was

355
00:14:25,880 --> 00:14:27,798
aggressive, became a very good athlete,

356
00:14:27,840 --> 00:14:30,133
and he's very competitive. He really likes to win,

357
00:14:30,175 --> 00:14:32,080
and his mother is like that as well.

358
00:14:32,320 --> 00:14:36,000
But he learned how to—that meant the aggression is

359
00:14:36,080 --> 00:14:39,975
still there, but it's replicated at a higher level

360
00:14:40,000 --> 00:14:41,560
of development that integrates it

361
00:14:41,601 --> 00:14:42,894
with all sorts of other things.

362
00:14:42,936 --> 00:14:44,979
If you want to be aggressive while you're playing

363
00:14:45,021 --> 00:14:46,856
a sport, you have to play it in a way

364
00:14:46,897 --> 00:14:49,280
that other people want to play with.

365
00:14:49,960 --> 00:14:51,880
Then you get to have your aggression,

366
00:14:52,280 --> 00:14:54,342
but in these walled boundaries.

367
00:14:54,367 --> 00:14:56,405
And partly what you're trying to do with your

368
00:14:56,447 --> 00:14:58,657
children is to teach them

369
00:14:59,040 --> 00:15:03,040
the sophisticated games that enable all of their

370
00:15:03,600 --> 00:15:05,000
needs and wants to be

371
00:15:06,120 --> 00:15:09,520
met over the longest possible span of time

372
00:15:09,720 --> 00:15:12,400
in the broadest possible set of situations.

373
00:15:12,961 --> 00:15:14,335
And that's not inhibition.

374
00:15:14,360 --> 00:15:16,000
It's not superego against id.

375
00:15:16,480 --> 00:15:18,695
It's the integration of those lower-order

376
00:15:18,720 --> 00:15:21,295
personalities into a higher-order

377
00:15:21,320 --> 00:15:24,872
personality that does meet all the demands.

378
00:15:25,081 --> 00:15:29,920
And so maybe by the time you're 13 or 14, 15,

379
00:15:30,200 --> 00:15:32,695
you're sophisticated enough as a male so that you

380
00:15:32,720 --> 00:15:34,615
can do a good job playing competitively

381
00:15:34,640 --> 00:15:37,095
on a sports team, and you're a good team player,

382
00:15:37,120 --> 00:15:39,255
and you give credit where credit is due,

383
00:15:39,280 --> 00:15:41,568
and you don't take all the glory when you win,

384
00:15:41,680 --> 00:15:43,840
and people like you, and you're a winner,

385
00:15:43,865 --> 00:15:45,405
and that makes you attractive.

386
00:15:45,440 --> 00:15:48,135
And so now your self-maintenance goals

387
00:15:48,160 --> 00:15:50,695
and the integration of your personality has also

388
00:15:50,720 --> 00:15:53,960
made you sexually and socially attractive, right?

389
00:15:54,320 --> 00:15:56,695
And so then you're playing a very complex

390
00:15:56,720 --> 00:16:00,135
and sophisticated game that meets all

391
00:16:00,160 --> 00:16:02,377
of the requirements of those subordinate systems

392
00:16:02,419 --> 00:16:04,600
simultaneously, and even more importantly,

393
00:16:04,712 --> 00:16:07,175
does that in a way that enables other people to do

394
00:16:07,200 --> 00:16:09,335
it at the same time, and maybe even better

395
00:16:09,360 --> 00:16:11,718
than they could if you weren't around.

396
00:16:12,093 --> 00:16:14,360
Right, and so, when you think your personality,

397
00:16:14,385 --> 00:16:16,840
you might think your personality has a goal.

398
00:16:16,931 --> 00:16:19,558
That's an interesting way of thinking about it.

399
00:16:19,600 --> 00:16:21,360
You can see what your goal is,

400
00:16:21,726 --> 00:16:23,895
the intrinsic goal of your personality,

401
00:16:23,920 --> 00:16:25,640
by asking yourself to imagine

402
00:16:25,800 --> 00:16:27,400
what it is that you might want.

403
00:16:28,080 --> 00:16:29,620
This is a very good exercise.

404
00:16:29,817 --> 00:16:31,193
We'll talk about this tomorrow,

405
00:16:31,234 --> 00:16:32,110
practically speaking.

406
00:16:32,152 --> 00:16:34,015
But you could imagine, daydream, you know.

407
00:16:34,040 --> 00:16:36,895
If your life could be set up the way that you

408
00:16:36,920 --> 00:16:38,535
wanted it to, we're assuming you

409
00:16:38,560 --> 00:16:40,540
bring a bit of wisdom to bear on this.

410
00:16:40,640 --> 00:16:42,491
Well, what would that look like?

411
00:16:42,920 --> 00:16:45,120
Probably you'd want to have a partner,

412
00:16:45,680 --> 00:16:47,340
and maybe you'd want her to like

413
00:16:47,400 --> 00:16:49,455
you, and maybe you'd like to have a family,

414
00:16:49,480 --> 00:16:51,251
and the same thing would apply there.

415
00:16:51,280 --> 00:16:52,935
You could get along with your parents.

416
00:16:52,960 --> 00:16:54,629
You could get along with your siblings.

417
00:16:54,671 --> 00:16:56,295
You love your children,

418
00:16:56,320 --> 00:16:57,673
and they would respect you.

419
00:16:57,715 --> 00:16:59,049
You'd have some friends.

420
00:16:59,091 --> 00:17:00,801
Well, if you could have the friends you wanted,

421
00:17:00,842 --> 00:17:01,802
what would that look like?

422
00:17:01,843 --> 00:17:03,303
And what would your friendships be like?

423
00:17:03,344 --> 00:17:04,971
You could do that with your career,

424
00:17:05,013 --> 00:17:06,597
and you can do that with your education.

425
00:17:06,639 --> 00:17:08,224
We'll step through this tomorrow when we

426
00:17:08,265 --> 00:17:10,684
talk about these things more concretely.

427
00:17:10,920 --> 00:17:13,520
But those are all those visions

428
00:17:15,160 --> 00:17:16,525
of what you want and need,

429
00:17:16,564 --> 00:17:18,399
if you're asking yourself honestly,

430
00:17:18,440 --> 00:17:20,442
are the collective voice

431
00:17:20,480 --> 00:17:23,360
of your integrated instincts that are attempting

432
00:17:23,480 --> 00:17:27,575
to lay out a description of who you could be if

433
00:17:27,600 --> 00:17:29,520
you could satisfy everything that needs

434
00:17:29,580 --> 00:17:31,840
to be satisfied at the same time.

435
00:17:32,661 --> 00:17:34,787
Now, you imagine it's three in the morning

436
00:17:34,829 --> 00:17:36,500
and you've done something stupid

437
00:17:36,712 --> 00:17:38,600
and your conscience comes to visit;

438
00:17:39,124 --> 00:17:40,775
and it's bothering you because

439
00:17:40,800 --> 00:17:42,969
you are a fool and you know it.

440
00:17:43,469 --> 00:17:44,760
You might say, well, what

441
00:17:45,160 --> 00:17:47,160
the hell is that voice of conscience?

442
00:17:48,520 --> 00:17:50,000
Is it you?

443
00:17:50,600 --> 00:17:53,175
And if it's you, why can't you just shut it off?

444
00:17:53,200 --> 00:17:56,495
And if it's you, why is it calling you to task?

445
00:17:56,520 --> 00:17:59,141
Why can't you just tell your conscience,

446
00:17:59,920 --> 00:18:01,601
"Reorient yourself there, buddy.

447
00:18:01,643 --> 00:18:03,175
I can do whatever the hell I want.

448
00:18:03,200 --> 00:18:05,271
I don't want to feel guilty about it afterwards.

449
00:18:05,313 --> 00:18:06,647
I don't want to feel disgusted

450
00:18:06,689 --> 00:18:08,360
or ashamed or that I'm lesser.

451
00:18:08,440 --> 00:18:10,025
Why would I bother with that?"

452
00:18:10,120 --> 00:18:11,914
And if your conscience is you,

453
00:18:12,080 --> 00:18:14,680
in some simple sense, why doesn't it just listen,

454
00:18:15,320 --> 00:18:16,447
which it doesn't?

455
00:18:16,920 --> 00:18:19,158
And the answer is something like,

456
00:18:20,080 --> 00:18:21,960
the person you could be,

457
00:18:22,560 --> 00:18:25,400
if you were all the things you could be,

458
00:18:26,040 --> 00:18:30,495
is calling you to task for your shortcomings

459
00:18:30,520 --> 00:18:33,360
in relationship to that domain of possibility.

460
00:18:34,000 --> 00:18:36,535
And you could think about that as—one way

461
00:18:36,560 --> 00:18:37,631
of thinking about that is

462
00:18:37,673 --> 00:18:39,508
that that's your higher self.

463
00:18:40,200 --> 00:18:41,975
Carl Jung made a distinction between

464
00:18:42,000 --> 00:18:44,440
the persona and the ego and the self.

465
00:18:44,960 --> 00:18:48,055
So the persona is what you show

466
00:18:48,080 --> 00:18:49,702
of yourself to other people.

467
00:18:50,160 --> 00:18:51,810
Now, that can be a falsehood,

468
00:18:51,852 --> 00:18:53,478
in which case you're manipulative,

469
00:18:53,520 --> 00:18:55,813
or it can be the sort of thing that you do when

470
00:18:55,855 --> 00:18:57,731
you go to visit the teller at a bank,

471
00:18:57,760 --> 00:18:59,775
because the teller says, "How are you?"

472
00:18:59,800 --> 00:19:01,359
And they don't really care.

473
00:19:01,400 --> 00:19:04,300
And you say, "I'm fine," even though you're not.

474
00:19:04,325 --> 00:19:05,975
And the reason you do that isn't

475
00:19:06,000 --> 00:19:07,156
because you're both lying.

476
00:19:07,198 --> 00:19:08,935
It's because the teller wants to see,

477
00:19:08,960 --> 00:19:10,409
"Are you sane enough

478
00:19:10,680 --> 00:19:14,535
to play the simplest of social games so that I can

479
00:19:14,560 --> 00:19:16,775
be reasonably certain that when I do my small

480
00:19:16,800 --> 00:19:18,832
task with you, all hell won't break loose?"

481
00:19:18,874 --> 00:19:20,320
And so they say, "How are you?"

482
00:19:20,345 --> 00:19:22,680
And if you say, "I'm fine," they think, "Well,

483
00:19:23,200 --> 00:19:25,196
you got the basics down.

484
00:19:25,279 --> 00:19:27,339
It's probably safe to proceed."

485
00:19:27,381 --> 00:19:29,174
Well, that's what small talk is for.

486
00:19:29,216 --> 00:19:31,718
And you need to have a persona because lots

487
00:19:31,760 --> 00:19:33,970
of time when you're interacting with other people,

488
00:19:34,012 --> 00:19:35,638
they don't want to know who you are.

489
00:19:35,664 --> 00:19:38,015
You don't want to know everything

490
00:19:38,040 --> 00:19:40,560
about the person who's selling clothes.

491
00:19:41,840 --> 00:19:45,055
When you're on a bus and someone sits down beside

492
00:19:45,080 --> 00:19:47,680
you and starts telling you their life story,

493
00:19:48,320 --> 00:19:50,280
you know that's not good.

494
00:19:50,920 --> 00:19:54,655
You know that's not good, put it that way.

495
00:19:54,680 --> 00:19:56,055
So that's the persona.

496
00:19:56,080 --> 00:19:58,480
And you want to have a well-manicured persona

497
00:19:58,720 --> 00:20:00,655
just so you're not a pain in the neck.

498
00:20:00,680 --> 00:20:02,786
You don't want to confuse yourself with that.

499
00:20:02,827 --> 00:20:04,621
You're not your social role.

500
00:20:04,800 --> 00:20:06,535
Then you have the ego behind that.

501
00:20:06,560 --> 00:20:10,417
And the ego is more like who you think you are.

502
00:20:10,709 --> 00:20:12,375
And that's a partial thing, too,

503
00:20:12,400 --> 00:20:14,796
because what the hell do you know about yourself?

504
00:20:14,837 --> 00:20:17,089
You probably don't know much about yourself, more

505
00:20:17,131 --> 00:20:19,299
about yourself than you know about anybody else.

506
00:20:19,341 --> 00:20:22,240
You're very, very, very complicated.

507
00:20:22,719 --> 00:20:25,471
You just think about the internal machinery.

508
00:20:25,555 --> 00:20:28,535
All the subsystems that make up you, and then that

509
00:20:28,560 --> 00:20:31,215
going all the way down to the subatomic level.

510
00:20:31,240 --> 00:20:33,520
Man, your brain is more complicated than

511
00:20:33,640 --> 00:20:36,880
anything else that exists, except other brains.

512
00:20:37,393 --> 00:20:38,880
You're one complicated thing.

513
00:20:39,560 --> 00:20:41,200
There are more connections,

514
00:20:41,568 --> 00:20:43,935
patterns of connections in your brain than there

515
00:20:43,960 --> 00:20:46,530
are subatomic particles in the visible universe.

516
00:20:47,080 --> 00:20:48,920
So that's how complicated you are.

517
00:20:49,960 --> 00:20:52,095
And that's why your wife or your husband

518
00:20:52,120 --> 00:20:53,760
can hardly stand living with you.

519
00:20:54,118 --> 00:20:59,760
And so the thing that holds you responsible,

520
00:21:00,160 --> 00:21:01,918
your conscience, let's say,

521
00:21:01,960 --> 00:21:05,455
that's what you could become.

522
00:21:05,480 --> 00:21:07,575
That's the unity that you could become

523
00:21:07,600 --> 00:21:10,360
attempting to make itself manifest in the moment.

524
00:21:10,760 --> 00:21:12,927
It does that all sorts of interesting ways.

525
00:21:12,960 --> 00:21:14,820
This is such a cool thing to know.

526
00:21:15,120 --> 00:21:17,681
It does that by calling you on your misbehavior.

527
00:21:18,080 --> 00:21:20,200
Now, your conscience can malfunction,

528
00:21:20,225 --> 00:21:22,735
because you can be socialized in a way that makes

529
00:21:22,760 --> 00:21:24,200
you too harsh on yourself,

530
00:21:24,520 --> 00:21:26,535
or maybe you've lied to yourself a bunch,

531
00:21:26,560 --> 00:21:28,255
and so you've warped your relationship

532
00:21:28,280 --> 00:21:30,760
with your internal guidance system.

533
00:21:31,193 --> 00:21:33,300
It's another reason you shouldn't lie,

534
00:21:33,800 --> 00:21:36,840
because you program yourself erroneously,

535
00:21:36,960 --> 00:21:39,840
and then you will report falsely to yourself.

536
00:21:40,320 --> 00:21:42,494
And then one day you'll be in real trouble,

537
00:21:42,600 --> 00:21:44,615
and you'll need to know what's true,

538
00:21:44,640 --> 00:21:46,247
and you won't be able to tell,

539
00:21:46,289 --> 00:21:48,457
and then you'll be in real trouble.

540
00:21:48,582 --> 00:21:51,160
So one of the reasons you don't lie is because you

541
00:21:51,185 --> 00:21:53,200
want to keep your vision clear,

542
00:21:53,440 --> 00:21:55,838
because you're going to need it at some point.

543
00:21:55,888 --> 00:21:58,695
OK, so imagine that your conscience will call

544
00:21:58,720 --> 00:22:01,240
you out on deviations from the proper course.

545
00:22:02,000 --> 00:22:04,470
OK, and I already defined the proper course.

546
00:22:04,640 --> 00:22:05,640
The proper course

547
00:22:06,120 --> 00:22:08,160
solves the problems you need to solve

548
00:22:09,000 --> 00:22:10,600
over the medium to long run

549
00:22:11,280 --> 00:22:13,720
and in relationship to all the other problems,

550
00:22:14,480 --> 00:22:16,215
for you, in a way that's

551
00:22:16,240 --> 00:22:17,920
maximally socially acceptable.

552
00:22:19,040 --> 00:22:20,720
It's a very complicated dynamic.

553
00:22:20,960 --> 00:22:21,960
It's something

554
00:22:23,520 --> 00:22:25,920
like being an athlete on multiple teams.

555
00:22:26,322 --> 00:22:28,480
Maybe it's something like being an athlete

556
00:22:28,505 --> 00:22:31,320
on multiple teams and performing well in school.

557
00:22:32,200 --> 00:22:34,400
You could see that there's a pattern there.

558
00:22:34,840 --> 00:22:36,920
You'd be a good athlete and good student,

559
00:22:37,304 --> 00:22:39,014
and the pattern would be good.

560
00:22:39,515 --> 00:22:39,840
Good.

561
00:22:40,015 --> 00:22:41,415
Good athlete, good student,

562
00:22:41,440 --> 00:22:43,753
and then that would decompose into the various

563
00:22:43,795 --> 00:22:46,339
sports team memberships and the various academic

564
00:22:46,480 --> 00:22:48,399
disciplines that you're excelling in.

565
00:22:48,440 --> 00:22:50,055
It's a hierarchy.

566
00:22:50,080 --> 00:22:51,095
Well, that hierarchy

567
00:22:51,120 --> 00:22:55,000
of attainment is your identity.

568
00:22:55,320 --> 00:22:58,880
And insofar as you've been true to yourself, then

569
00:22:59,640 --> 00:23:02,185
that's going to be successful and differentiated.

570
00:23:02,371 --> 00:23:04,735
OK, so your conscience will call

571
00:23:04,760 --> 00:23:06,440
you on deviations from that path.

572
00:23:06,731 --> 00:23:08,380
So that's a good thing to know.

573
00:23:08,405 --> 00:23:12,120
That's like the voice of the higher self within.

574
00:23:12,193 --> 00:23:13,695
That's a religious phenomenon,

575
00:23:13,720 --> 00:23:15,822
one of the things you see happening in the Old

576
00:23:15,863 --> 00:23:18,400
Testament, for example, with the Prophet Elijah.

577
00:23:18,929 --> 00:23:22,215
Elijah is the first person in the Judeo-Christian

578
00:23:22,240 --> 00:23:23,935
pantheon who identifies

579
00:23:23,960 --> 00:23:25,740
the voice of God with conscience.

580
00:23:26,440 --> 00:23:28,295
So he's a prophet that stands

581
00:23:28,320 --> 00:23:29,625
up against the nature god.

582
00:23:29,666 --> 00:23:32,120
So before that, one of the presuppositions of

583
00:23:32,680 --> 00:23:37,548
the archaic pagans was that the divine was

584
00:23:37,590 --> 00:23:38,924
embedded in the natural world,

585
00:23:38,966 --> 00:23:39,883
the force of nature.

586
00:23:39,925 --> 00:23:41,093
And you can imagine that.

587
00:23:41,134 --> 00:23:42,886
You go look at the Grand Canyon; it

588
00:23:42,920 --> 00:23:43,970
inspires you with awe.

589
00:23:44,012 --> 00:23:45,888
And you look at the stars and the ocean;

590
00:23:45,914 --> 00:23:47,583
you experience a hurricane.

591
00:23:47,608 --> 00:23:49,215
You could see that you could

592
00:23:49,240 --> 00:23:51,400
place divinity in the natural world.

593
00:23:51,962 --> 00:23:53,535
Elijah was the first person,

594
00:23:53,560 --> 00:23:56,600
at least in this pantheon of stories, who

595
00:23:58,120 --> 00:24:00,067
made a psychological interpretation,

596
00:24:00,200 --> 00:24:02,027
said the thing that should orient you

597
00:24:02,160 --> 00:24:03,880
most properly is the still,

598
00:24:03,905 --> 00:24:06,364
small voice within, the voice of conscience.

599
00:24:07,114 --> 00:24:08,855
And so that's a very interesting

600
00:24:08,880 --> 00:24:09,908
thing to know, right?

601
00:24:09,950 --> 00:24:13,360
And you think, well, what's that a reflection of?

602
00:24:14,720 --> 00:24:16,775
Well, it's not you, as we said,

603
00:24:16,800 --> 00:24:19,040
because if it was you, you could control it.

604
00:24:19,124 --> 00:24:21,793
It's got an autonomy, your conscience.

605
00:24:21,840 --> 00:24:22,960
It speaks to you.

606
00:24:23,360 --> 00:24:25,280
It'll hold you accountable.

607
00:24:25,960 --> 00:24:27,923
Well, you have to ask yourself,

608
00:24:28,123 --> 00:24:30,700
well, what is it that's holding you accountable?

609
00:24:31,468 --> 00:24:32,775
And you could say, well,

610
00:24:32,800 --> 00:24:34,680
it's the voice of society within.

611
00:24:35,221 --> 00:24:36,015
It's like, well,

612
00:24:36,040 --> 00:24:37,890
that's not really much of an answer, actually,

613
00:24:37,932 --> 00:24:39,349
because then you have to ask, well,

614
00:24:39,391 --> 00:24:41,815
where did the voice of society come from?

615
00:24:41,840 --> 00:24:43,889
What's the derivation of that spirit?

616
00:24:44,600 --> 00:24:47,023
Because then that would be tradition extending

617
00:24:47,064 --> 00:24:48,320
over thousands and thousands

618
00:24:48,345 --> 00:24:49,937
or tens of thousands of years.

619
00:24:50,521 --> 00:24:52,640
It doesn't really dissolve the mystery.

620
00:24:53,148 --> 00:24:55,615
If it's the voice of society within, it's

621
00:24:55,640 --> 00:24:59,613
the voice of the proper social orientation within.

622
00:25:00,197 --> 00:25:01,535
So then it's the spirit

623
00:25:01,560 --> 00:25:03,242
of proper social orientation.

624
00:25:03,325 --> 00:25:05,500
You still end up with the same problem.

625
00:25:05,680 --> 00:25:08,080
It's an autonomous spirit of some sort.

626
00:25:08,249 --> 00:25:09,708
And so it's the thing that will

627
00:25:09,750 --> 00:25:11,200
call on your misbehavior.

628
00:25:11,640 --> 00:25:13,895
There's another element to it,

629
00:25:13,920 --> 00:25:15,296
too, that's worth knowing about.

630
00:25:15,338 --> 00:25:17,048
So I'll tell you another story.

631
00:25:17,160 --> 00:25:19,341
So this is from Exodus, again.

632
00:25:20,320 --> 00:25:22,360
So Moses is going about his business

633
00:25:22,800 --> 00:25:24,440
in Exodus as a shepherd.

634
00:25:25,000 --> 00:25:27,264
And that was actually a pretty admirable

635
00:25:27,480 --> 00:25:30,160
occupation in archaic times because

636
00:25:30,600 --> 00:25:32,977
sheep are hard to take care of and there's lambs,

637
00:25:33,019 --> 00:25:34,520
they're hard to take care of and

638
00:25:34,562 --> 00:25:35,480
they're delicious.

639
00:25:35,520 --> 00:25:38,320
And so there's lions and wolves around

640
00:25:38,720 --> 00:25:41,655
the Middle East at that time and plenty of them.

641
00:25:41,693 --> 00:25:43,111
And so if you were a shepherd,

642
00:25:43,153 --> 00:25:45,335
you had to take care of yourself and you

643
00:25:45,360 --> 00:25:47,281
had to protect the lambs from lions.

644
00:25:47,406 --> 00:25:48,895
And that was hard.

645
00:25:48,920 --> 00:25:50,680
So you were like a major league

646
00:25:50,840 --> 00:25:52,695
character if you could manage that.

647
00:25:52,720 --> 00:25:54,895
It was a relatively low-status job,

648
00:25:54,920 --> 00:25:57,160
but that didn't mean it wasn't difficult.

649
00:25:57,540 --> 00:25:59,560
You could see that it would be an analogy

650
00:25:59,585 --> 00:26:01,095
for protecting the vulnerable

651
00:26:01,120 --> 00:26:03,360
from the worst of all possible predators.

652
00:26:03,837 --> 00:26:05,671
That's why the shepherd, for example,

653
00:26:05,713 --> 00:26:07,680
is an analog to the savior, for example,

654
00:26:07,715 --> 00:26:09,341
in the Judeo-Christian pantheon.

655
00:26:09,400 --> 00:26:12,415
Anyways, Moses has left Egypt temporarily.

656
00:26:12,440 --> 00:26:16,600
He killed some Egyptian who was torturing a

657
00:26:17,320 --> 00:26:19,568
Hebrew slave, and he had to make tracks.

658
00:26:19,651 --> 00:26:21,735
And so he went to this foreign country,

659
00:26:21,760 --> 00:26:23,655
and he got himself a couple of wives.

660
00:26:23,680 --> 00:26:25,855
And he had a father-in-law he got along with,

661
00:26:25,897 --> 00:26:27,106
and he established a life there.

662
00:26:27,148 --> 00:26:28,899
And so he's wondering around being a shepherd,

663
00:26:28,941 --> 00:26:30,359
feeling pretty good about himself.

664
00:26:30,400 --> 00:26:33,028
And something beckons to him.

665
00:26:33,360 --> 00:26:36,695
Something captures his attention off to the side.

666
00:26:36,720 --> 00:26:37,760
It's a burning bush.

667
00:26:37,785 --> 00:26:39,680
Now, it's not like an oak tree on fire

668
00:26:39,705 --> 00:26:41,375
right in the middle of his path.

669
00:26:41,400 --> 00:26:45,040
It's something that you could pass by.

670
00:26:45,913 --> 00:26:48,165
Now, a burning bush, what does that mean?

671
00:26:48,200 --> 00:26:49,695
Well, a bush is a little tree,

672
00:26:49,720 --> 00:26:52,080
and a tree is commonly a symbol of life,

673
00:26:52,440 --> 00:26:53,962
partly because life branches,

674
00:26:54,003 --> 00:26:56,005
partly because a tree is alive, partly because

675
00:26:56,047 --> 00:26:58,255
we lived in trees for 20 million years.

676
00:26:58,280 --> 00:27:01,485
We have a very integral relationship with trees.

677
00:27:01,600 --> 00:27:02,820
That's why we think of

678
00:27:03,200 --> 00:27:05,415
old growth forests as sacred.

679
00:27:05,440 --> 00:27:07,920
We have a very tight relationship with trees.

680
00:27:08,320 --> 00:27:09,860
A tree is a symbol of life,

681
00:27:10,280 --> 00:27:13,747
a symbol of being, let's say, of living being.

682
00:27:14,240 --> 00:27:16,320
And fire is a symbol of transformation.

683
00:27:16,520 --> 00:27:19,335
And so, a burning bush is something

684
00:27:19,360 --> 00:27:21,526
living so intensely that it's in flame.

685
00:27:21,680 --> 00:27:24,758
It's a compelling—you know how compelling fire is.

686
00:27:24,840 --> 00:27:26,781
You can't take your eyes off fire.

687
00:27:26,840 --> 00:27:28,840
And so this is something compelling that

688
00:27:29,560 --> 00:27:31,815
calls to Moses, and he deviates from his path,

689
00:27:31,840 --> 00:27:33,286
and he goes to investigate.

690
00:27:33,320 --> 00:27:35,560
OK, so when does that happen in your life?

691
00:27:36,000 --> 00:27:38,540
It happens when you get interested in something.

692
00:27:38,791 --> 00:27:40,760
And you see, that has an autonomy, too.

693
00:27:41,120 --> 00:27:44,495
Maybe you're 15 and you're in class and a new girl

694
00:27:44,520 --> 00:27:46,130
comes in and it's like, man,

695
00:27:46,172 --> 00:27:48,000
you're instantly interested in her.

696
00:27:48,132 --> 00:27:48,882
It's like, well,

697
00:27:48,924 --> 00:27:50,384
where the hell did that come from?

698
00:27:50,425 --> 00:27:51,718
It's not you.

699
00:27:51,760 --> 00:27:52,535
Not exactly.

700
00:27:52,560 --> 00:27:54,600
Maybe you're not even happy about it.

701
00:27:54,971 --> 00:27:56,180
I mean, that happens in all

702
00:27:56,222 --> 00:27:57,848
sorts of doomed relationships.

703
00:27:57,890 --> 00:28:01,080
You get interested in someone, and it's hopeless

704
00:28:01,351 --> 00:28:03,335
