00:41:49,345 --> 00:41:50,895
Maybe they're not the worst.

1065
00:41:50,920 --> 00:41:52,180
They're up there, though.

1066
00:41:52,440 --> 00:41:54,960
And you can take the worst psychopathic criminals,

1067
00:41:55,400 --> 00:41:57,455
so the people who treat other people

1068
00:41:57,480 --> 00:42:00,050
and themselves with the utmost contempt,

1069
00:42:00,425 --> 00:42:02,427
and how do you punish them?

1070
00:42:03,080 --> 00:42:05,180
By putting them in solitary confinement.

1071
00:42:05,560 --> 00:42:07,520
That's how social people are.

1072
00:42:08,015 --> 00:42:11,060
You can take the worst antisocial person

1073
00:42:11,393 --> 00:42:13,770
and punish them by isolating them.

1074
00:42:14,120 --> 00:42:16,840
And you're not the worst antisocial person.

1075
00:42:17,520 --> 00:42:20,735
So you imagine how important being properly

1076
00:42:20,760 --> 00:42:23,361
embedded in the social environment is to you.

1077
00:42:23,440 --> 00:42:25,840
There's no getting your act together without

1078
00:42:26,520 --> 00:42:28,815
working that at multiple

1079
00:42:28,840 --> 00:42:30,160
levels of social existence.

1080
00:42:30,680 --> 00:42:33,120
There's no being sane in a toxic relationship.

1081
00:42:34,080 --> 00:42:35,415
That's not going to happen.

1082
00:42:35,440 --> 00:42:37,240
You've got to drop the idea.

1083
00:42:37,289 --> 00:42:39,575
Part of the reason that you want to treat other

1084
00:42:39,600 --> 00:42:41,793
people the way you would want to be treated is

1085
00:42:41,835 --> 00:42:44,087
because there's no difference between the two.

1086
00:42:44,120 --> 00:42:45,178
So, for example,

1087
00:42:45,560 --> 00:42:48,640
if you establish—let's say you go out of your way

1088
00:42:50,040 --> 00:42:51,740
to be of service to other people,

1089
00:42:52,400 --> 00:42:56,520
and you might contrast that with being selfish.

1090
00:42:57,520 --> 00:42:59,735
OK, but what's the consequence of that?

1091
00:42:59,760 --> 00:43:01,655
Let's think it through for a minute.

1092
00:43:01,680 --> 00:43:02,940
There's only one of you.

1093
00:43:03,120 --> 00:43:04,854
There's a lot of other people.

1094
00:43:05,080 --> 00:43:07,175
OK, so now imagine you're running around,

1095
00:43:07,200 --> 00:43:08,816
trying to make yourself the most

1096
00:43:08,857 --> 00:43:10,942
useful possible to other people.

1097
00:43:11,280 --> 00:43:13,480
OK, and you do that for, like, 1,000 people.

1098
00:43:14,720 --> 00:43:18,044
Well, 900 of those people are going

1099
00:43:18,073 --> 00:43:20,575
to be heavily inclined to reciprocate.

1100
00:43:20,701 --> 00:43:22,960
So now you've put yourself in a position where

1101
00:43:22,985 --> 00:43:26,240
there's only one of you, and there's 900 people

1102
00:43:27,280 --> 00:43:29,720
trying to do for you what you've done for them.

1103
00:43:30,160 --> 00:43:31,668
That's a good deal.

1104
00:43:32,360 --> 00:43:34,415
When your kids, when they're teenagers,

1105
00:43:34,440 --> 00:43:36,130
they're striving to be popular.

1106
00:43:36,172 --> 00:43:38,590
That's not exactly what they're striving for.

1107
00:43:38,632 --> 00:43:41,843
And popularity isn't some sort of shallow virtue.

1108
00:43:41,920 --> 00:43:44,480
It's like, if your kids can be of proper service

1109
00:43:44,600 --> 00:43:47,295
to their peers, they're going to be surrounded

1110
00:43:47,320 --> 00:43:50,400
by people who are thrilled to have them around.

1111
00:43:51,120 --> 00:43:53,655
Yeah, well, if you were surrounded all the time

1112
00:43:53,680 --> 00:43:55,813
by people who are thrilled to have you around,

1113
00:43:55,840 --> 00:43:57,064
you wouldn't have to be worried

1114
00:43:57,106 --> 00:43:58,095
about your mental health.

1115
00:43:58,148 --> 00:44:00,067
That'd pretty much take care of itself.

1116
00:44:00,160 --> 00:44:01,640
There is a corollary to that.

1117
00:44:01,776 --> 00:44:03,840
When psychologists started to investigate

1118
00:44:03,920 --> 00:44:06,880
the structure of self-definitional

1119
00:44:08,680 --> 00:44:11,255
descriptors, self-definitional adjectives—sad,

1120
00:44:11,280 --> 00:44:15,295
happy, dutiful, creative—they

1121
00:44:15,320 --> 00:44:16,997
noticed that they clumped in bin.

1122
00:44:17,039 --> 00:44:18,415
So if you're happy, you're

1123
00:44:18,520 --> 00:44:19,895
more likely to be talkative.

1124
00:44:19,920 --> 00:44:22,080
If you're angry, you're more likely to be sad.

1125
00:44:22,210 --> 00:44:23,876
If you're creative, you're more

1126
00:44:23,901 --> 00:44:26,005
likely to be interested in ideas.

1127
00:44:26,047 --> 00:44:27,295
If you're dutiful, you're

1128
00:44:27,320 --> 00:44:28,716
more likely to be patriotic.

1129
00:44:28,760 --> 00:44:29,480
Things clump.

1130
00:44:31,440 --> 00:44:35,040
Self-consciousness clumps with misery,

1131
00:44:36,280 --> 00:44:40,695
right, so tightly in the NEO-PI-R,

1132
00:44:40,720 --> 00:44:43,495
which is a five-dimensional personality inventory,

1133
00:44:43,520 --> 00:44:45,229
one of the canonical inventories,

1134
00:44:45,360 --> 00:44:49,240
one of the facets of neuroticism,

1135
00:44:49,440 --> 00:44:51,640
which is the proclivity for negative emotion,

1136
00:44:51,665 --> 00:44:53,575
they all clump, the negative emotions,

1137
00:44:53,600 --> 00:44:54,860
is self-consciousness.

1138
00:44:55,120 --> 00:44:56,360
So here's the situation.

1139
00:44:57,000 --> 00:44:59,520
The more you think about your narrow self,

1140
00:44:59,575 --> 00:45:01,618
the more miserable you are.

1141
00:45:01,880 --> 00:45:04,360
And it's not causal, exactly.

1142
00:45:05,080 --> 00:45:08,040
They're not distinguishable from one another.

1143
00:45:08,400 --> 00:45:10,855
There's no difference between being

1144
00:45:10,880 --> 00:45:13,560
hyper-concerned with your immediate self

1145
00:45:14,040 --> 00:45:15,421
and being miserable.

1146
00:45:15,463 --> 00:45:17,631
Now, you might ask, "What's the way out of that?"

1147
00:45:17,673 --> 00:45:18,632
And you might say, "Well,

1148
00:45:18,674 --> 00:45:19,925
stop thinking about yourself."

1149
00:45:19,967 --> 00:45:22,010
And if I tell you to stop thinking about

1150
00:45:22,040 --> 00:45:24,012
yourself and you try that, you're just going to

1151
00:45:24,053 --> 00:45:26,013
think about yourself not thinking about yourself.

1152
00:45:26,055 --> 00:45:27,139
And so you're going to be

1153
00:45:27,181 --> 00:45:28,599
thinking about yourself nonstop.

1154
00:45:28,641 --> 00:45:29,641
It doesn't work.

1155
00:45:29,683 --> 00:45:31,977
One of the things you can do with socially anxious

1156
00:45:32,018 --> 00:45:33,978
people, this is a good thing to know,

1157
00:45:34,360 --> 00:45:35,160
a practical tip.

1158
00:45:35,520 --> 00:45:37,095
If you're anxious at parties,

1159
00:45:37,120 --> 00:45:39,358
you're worried about how other people are reacting

1160
00:45:39,399 --> 00:45:41,646
to you, start trying to make them comfortable.

1161
00:45:43,120 --> 00:45:44,080
Forget about you.

1162
00:45:45,080 --> 00:45:46,495
But don't forget about you

1163
00:45:46,520 --> 00:45:48,449
the way, like, consciously.

1164
00:45:48,616 --> 00:45:50,617
Focus on the other people and think, "OK,

1165
00:45:50,659 --> 00:45:53,335
how could I make this person feel

1166
00:45:53,360 --> 00:45:55,095
as welcome as possible right now?"

1167
00:45:55,120 --> 00:45:56,240
Listening to people,

1168
00:45:56,289 --> 00:45:57,790
by the way, that really works.

1169
00:45:57,832 --> 00:45:59,458
You can ask people questions.

1170
00:45:59,500 --> 00:46:01,084
There's so many people out there

1171
00:46:01,126 --> 00:46:02,460
that never get listened to.

1172
00:46:02,502 --> 00:46:05,295
If you can listen 10% better than the typical

1173
00:46:05,320 --> 00:46:06,935
person, you'll be so popular,

1174
00:46:06,960 --> 00:46:08,506
you won't be able to stand it.

1175
00:46:08,549 --> 00:46:09,925
So you could just start with—"I

1176
00:46:09,967 --> 00:46:11,218
don't have anything to say."

1177
00:46:11,259 --> 00:46:12,427
It's like, that's OK.

1178
00:46:12,600 --> 00:46:15,054
Ask stupid questions and listen.

1179
00:46:15,360 --> 00:46:17,095
People will be so happy,

1180
00:46:17,120 --> 00:46:19,475
they'll just talk you to death.

1181
00:46:20,840 --> 00:46:25,840
OK, so your instincts, your basic motivations

1182
00:46:26,360 --> 00:46:28,375
grip this whole perceptual frame.

1183
00:46:28,400 --> 00:46:30,400
They establish the aim, but they determine

1184
00:46:30,442 --> 00:46:32,415
what you see and how you feel about it.

1185
00:46:32,440 --> 00:46:35,071
I'll show you how that works here.

1186
00:46:35,282 --> 00:46:37,200
OK, so you're in one of these frames.

1187
00:46:37,600 --> 00:46:39,199
What do you see in the world?

1188
00:46:39,241 --> 00:46:40,200
You're hungry.

1189
00:46:40,784 --> 00:46:44,480
Well, you're happy to see a butter knife.

1190
00:46:44,746 --> 00:46:46,775
You're happy to see a loaf of bread.

1191
00:46:46,800 --> 00:46:50,120
Those are tools that will enable you to fulfill

1192
00:46:51,080 --> 00:46:53,128
the demand of the frame.

1193
00:46:53,169 --> 00:46:54,600
When you go into the kitchen,

1194
00:46:54,625 --> 00:46:58,135
your perception will narrow so that all you see

1195
00:46:58,160 --> 00:47:01,440
are the facilitators of your desire

1196
00:47:02,280 --> 00:47:03,553
and the obstacles.

1197
00:47:03,602 --> 00:47:06,015
The facilitators will fill you with positive

1198
00:47:06,040 --> 00:47:07,389
emotion, and the obstacles will

1199
00:47:07,431 --> 00:47:08,807
fill you with negative emotion.

1200
00:47:08,849 --> 00:47:10,309
That's how you evaluate the world.

1201
00:47:10,350 --> 00:47:11,601
You have a frame

1202
00:47:11,726 --> 00:47:13,920
that sets up the perceptual objects.

1203
00:47:14,229 --> 00:47:16,314
The frame has a goal and a starting point.

1204
00:47:16,355 --> 00:47:17,898
The starting point is where you are.

1205
00:47:17,940 --> 00:47:19,858
The goal is where you want to be,

1206
00:47:20,360 --> 00:47:22,320
in hand with a peanut butter sandwich.

1207
00:47:22,400 --> 00:47:23,320
That's your goal.

1208
00:47:23,800 --> 00:47:26,113
And then maybe your kid comes in and wants

1209
00:47:26,155 --> 00:47:28,157
to show you a picture and you're annoyed.

1210
00:47:28,198 --> 00:47:28,782
And why?

1211
00:47:28,824 --> 00:47:30,534
It's because you're trying to make

1212
00:47:30,560 --> 00:47:31,952
a damn peanut butter sandwich.

1213
00:47:31,993 --> 00:47:33,920
And so under normal circumstances,

1214
00:47:33,953 --> 00:47:35,640
maybe you'd be happy about that.

1215
00:47:36,000 --> 00:47:37,957
But because you're hungry and irritable,

1216
00:47:38,000 --> 00:47:41,055
the child's offering appears as

1217
00:47:41,080 --> 00:47:43,320
an obstacle and elicits negative emotion.

1218
00:47:44,000 --> 00:47:45,615
So it's very useful to know that.

1219
00:47:45,640 --> 00:47:47,855
You don't see the world as objects

1220
00:47:47,880 --> 00:47:49,760
and lay a structure value on it.

1221
00:47:50,280 --> 00:47:53,840
The world presents itself to you as pathways,

1222
00:47:54,160 --> 00:47:55,529
tools, and obstacles,

1223
00:47:55,555 --> 00:47:57,695
and then everything else that's invisible,

1224
00:47:57,720 --> 00:48:00,120
which is like 99.9% of everything.

1225
00:48:00,350 --> 00:48:02,535
And then you understand emotions as soon as

1226
00:48:02,560 --> 00:48:04,655
you understand that, which is also quite fun.

1227
00:48:04,680 --> 00:48:07,480
OK, so you go from point A to point B.

1228
00:48:07,523 --> 00:48:08,982
You're always doing that as long

1229
00:48:09,024 --> 00:48:10,484
as you're awake and conscious.

1230
00:48:10,525 --> 00:48:12,379
You're always on a journey somewhere,

1231
00:48:13,080 --> 00:48:14,080
micro journey maybe.

1232
00:48:15,405 --> 00:48:17,573
And you're always looking for things that will get

1233
00:48:17,615 --> 00:48:18,949
you to where you're going and things

1234
00:48:18,991 --> 00:48:19,992
that will get in your way.

1235
00:48:20,033 --> 00:48:21,743
The things that will get you to where you're

1236
00:48:21,785 --> 00:48:23,495
going, they fill you with positive emotion.

1237
00:48:23,520 --> 00:48:25,140
Two kinds of positive emotion.

1238
00:48:25,288 --> 00:48:27,335
There's the kind of emotion that emerges

1239
00:48:27,360 --> 00:48:29,374
when you get what you're after.

1240
00:48:29,640 --> 00:48:30,560
That's satiation.

1241
00:48:31,065 --> 00:48:33,000
So you eat a peanut butter sandwich,

1242
00:48:33,440 --> 00:48:34,360
you're satisfied.

1243
00:48:34,962 --> 00:48:37,465
The price you pay for that is the little frame you

1244
00:48:37,506 --> 00:48:38,966
were operating in that gives

1245
00:48:39,008 --> 00:48:40,920
your life purpose disappears.

1246
00:48:41,560 --> 00:48:44,455
So on graduation day at high school,

1247
00:48:44,480 --> 00:48:45,780
you're king of the castle,

1248
00:48:45,960 --> 00:48:50,095
and the next day, you're, like, cap in hand,

1249
00:48:50,120 --> 00:48:52,175
beggar, looking for a job at Starbucks.

1250
00:48:52,200 --> 00:48:53,629
But you see what I mean?

1251
00:48:54,130 --> 00:48:55,360
So you attain something,

1252
00:48:55,881 --> 00:48:58,509
and that is satisfying, but the price you pay

1253
00:48:58,534 --> 00:49:00,859
for that, it blows out the frame of reference.

1254
00:49:00,901 --> 00:49:02,277
It brings it to an end.

1255
00:49:02,320 --> 00:49:04,570
That's what satiation does,

1256
00:49:04,612 --> 00:49:06,900
and that's a particular kind of positive emotion.

1257
00:49:06,925 --> 00:49:08,532
The positive emotion that you

1258
00:49:08,574 --> 00:49:10,600
run on is more like hope.

1259
00:49:11,040 --> 00:49:14,815
The thing that makes us exhilarated or

1260
00:49:14,840 --> 00:49:18,920
enthusiastic or interested or curious or motivated

1261
00:49:19,280 --> 00:49:20,495
is the vision that we're

1262
00:49:20,520 --> 00:49:22,920
moving towards a valued goal.

1263
00:49:24,080 --> 00:49:27,015
OK, so now you've got to think about

1264
00:49:27,040 --> 00:49:28,831
that because there's corollaries.

1265
00:49:29,400 --> 00:49:31,615
The positive emotion that fills your life

1266
00:49:31,640 --> 00:49:33,595
with enthusiasm and hope is experienced

1267
00:49:33,640 --> 00:49:35,400
in relationship to a goal,

1268
00:49:35,800 --> 00:49:38,020
not as a consequence of its accomplishment.

1269
00:49:38,966 --> 00:49:41,720
OK, so the corollary is you should have a goal.

1270
00:49:42,977 --> 00:49:44,840
Another corollary is you should have

1271
00:49:44,865 --> 00:49:47,400
a goal that you can take steps towards.

1272
00:49:47,840 --> 00:49:50,180
Because if the goal is so damn impossible that

1273
00:49:50,400 --> 00:49:53,535
you can't take steps towards it, then the world

1274
00:49:53,560 --> 00:49:56,197
just lays itself out as a series of obstacles.

1275
00:49:56,240 --> 00:50:00,415
So if your goal is so stellar that you can't

1276
00:50:00,440 --> 00:50:03,760
move towards it, you should lower your goal.

1277
00:50:04,204 --> 00:50:06,400
You've bitten off more than you can chew.

1278
00:50:06,580 --> 00:50:08,815
And this is what you do with little kids.

1279
00:50:08,840 --> 00:50:11,168
If you want to encourage them to do something,

1280
00:50:11,209 --> 00:50:12,575
you set them a goal that's

1281
00:50:12,600 --> 00:50:14,880
within their domain of achievement,

1282
00:50:15,600 --> 00:50:16,960
but slightly difficult,

1283
00:50:18,080 --> 00:50:19,800
so that they can move towards it,

1284
00:50:20,720 --> 00:50:23,000
but it demands a bit, and they transform

1285
00:50:23,040 --> 00:50:24,760
themselves as they're pursuing it.

1286
00:50:24,880 --> 00:50:27,320
So a goal that you'll find optimally

1287
00:50:27,600 --> 00:50:29,120
meaningful will do two things.

1288
00:50:30,200 --> 00:50:31,435
It'll beckon to you.

1289
00:50:31,480 --> 00:50:32,820
You want to achieve it.

1290
00:50:33,019 --> 00:50:35,055
It'll produce positive emotion because

1291
00:50:35,080 --> 00:50:37,095
you can see yourself making movement.

1292
00:50:37,120 --> 00:50:39,000
But it'll be movement that pushes you

1293
00:50:39,318 --> 00:50:41,680
to transform, so that the next

1294
00:50:41,920 --> 00:50:43,781
goal that you chase will be better.

1295
00:50:44,960 --> 00:50:48,335
So that's another thing, why you don't have

1296
00:50:48,365 --> 00:50:50,534
to worry too much about what you're aiming at.

1297
00:50:50,575 --> 00:50:52,520
You do the best job you can.

1298
00:50:53,457 --> 00:50:54,655
What do you want?

1299
00:50:54,680 --> 00:50:55,913
OK, this is what I want.

1300
00:50:55,955 --> 00:50:56,706
Are you right?

1301
00:50:56,747 --> 00:50:58,457
You don't know, because what do you know?

1302
00:50:58,499 --> 00:50:59,625
But you decide to pursue it.

1303
00:50:59,666 --> 00:51:01,334
Then you break it down, so you have a name

1304
00:51:01,376 --> 00:51:04,240
that you could hypothetically move towards.

1305
00:51:04,880 --> 00:51:05,200
OK,

1306
00:51:05,880 --> 00:51:08,375
now you move towards it and you start to change

1307
00:51:08,400 --> 00:51:10,340
a little bit because of what you're learning.

1308
00:51:10,384 --> 00:51:11,468
OK, at some point, you're

1309
00:51:11,510 --> 00:51:12,695
going to change the goal.

1310
00:51:12,720 --> 00:51:14,178
So you can hold the goal

1311
00:51:14,345 --> 00:51:16,097
with something like a light touch,

1312
00:51:16,200 --> 00:51:18,815
knowing that it's not final, but also knowing that

1313
00:51:18,840 --> 00:51:21,295
even though it's not final, you should pursue it.

1314
00:51:21,320 --> 00:51:23,215
So, just like there's lots of pathways

1315
00:51:23,240 --> 00:51:26,105
into chaos—all you have to do is confront

1316
00:51:26,147 --> 00:51:28,482
something that's an impediment, it doesn't matter

1317
00:51:28,524 --> 00:51:31,318
what it is—there's a lot of pathways uphill.

1318
00:51:31,360 --> 00:51:34,095
So uphill is a particular direction,

1319
00:51:34,120 --> 00:51:35,800
but there's many entry points.

1320
00:51:36,320 --> 00:51:40,575
And as you enter one of those entry points and you

1321
00:51:40,600 --> 00:51:41,827
transform, you'll converge

1322
00:51:41,868 --> 00:51:43,720
on the proper goal across time.

1323
00:51:44,320 --> 00:51:46,040
You're going like this, error,

1324
00:51:46,440 --> 00:51:48,374
but it'll correct as you move forward.

1325
00:51:48,640 --> 00:51:51,585
So one of the things my clients used to ask me,

1326
00:51:51,626 --> 00:51:53,545
students, too, is, "I don't know what to do."

1327
00:51:53,586 --> 00:51:55,495
Well, then they'd be like that for 15 years.

1328
00:51:55,520 --> 00:51:57,673
"I never figured out what I should do."

1329
00:51:57,715 --> 00:52:00,717
Well, one thing you're doing is getting older.

1330
00:52:01,080 --> 00:52:04,440
Right, so there's no zero-cost stasis.

1331
00:52:04,971 --> 00:52:06,555
So if you're not moving ahead,

1332
00:52:06,597 --> 00:52:07,973
you are degenerating.

1333
00:52:08,280 --> 00:52:11,640
OK, so there's no staying where you are,

1334
00:52:11,810 --> 00:52:13,640
so then, you don't know what to do.

1335
00:52:13,665 --> 00:52:15,200
It's like, well, guess.

1336
00:52:15,229 --> 00:52:17,295
Let's see if we can come up with something that's

1337
00:52:17,320 --> 00:52:18,535
slightly better than whatever

1338
00:52:18,560 --> 00:52:19,855
the hell it is that you're doing.

1339
00:52:19,880 --> 00:52:21,720
We'll talk about this in more detail tomorrow,

1340
00:52:21,745 --> 00:52:23,778
about how you can get that ball rolling.

1341
00:52:23,820 --> 00:52:25,571
And you might think, well, "I don't want

1342
00:52:25,613 --> 00:52:27,695
to take the risk of aiming at the wrong thing."

1343
00:52:27,720 --> 00:52:29,775
It's like, you're going to aim at the wrong

1344
00:52:29,800 --> 00:52:31,701
thing, because what the hell do you know?

1345
00:52:31,743 --> 00:52:33,655
But if you aim at the wrong thing and you

1346
00:52:33,680 --> 00:52:35,246
practice, your aim will get better.

1347
00:52:35,288 --> 00:52:36,831
So don't worry about that too much.

1348
00:52:36,872 --> 00:52:38,791
It's like, pick something.

1349
00:52:39,080 --> 00:52:43,680
Pick some interesting disciplinary routine.

1350
00:52:43,962 --> 00:52:45,680
Now, this is a place where moral

1351
00:52:45,705 --> 00:52:47,738
relativism actually has its role.

1352
00:52:47,960 --> 00:52:50,055
You might say, well, there's a variety

1353
00:52:50,080 --> 00:52:52,260
of different forms of acceptable morality.

1354
00:52:52,302 --> 00:52:53,470
And obviously that's true,

1355
00:52:53,511 --> 00:52:55,471
because we each have a different personality.

1356
00:52:55,513 --> 00:52:57,765
So there's a fair bit of play in the moral system.

1357
00:52:57,807 --> 00:52:59,600
That doesn't mean it isn't oriented

1358
00:52:59,625 --> 00:53:01,435
toward something that's stellar.

1359
00:53:01,520 --> 00:53:03,775
What it means is, there's lots of games

1360
00:53:03,800 --> 00:53:05,646
that you can play that will work.

1361
00:53:05,840 --> 00:53:10,400
But the one game that doesn't work is no game,

1362
00:53:11,640 --> 00:53:13,335
because there's no progress there.

1363
00:53:13,360 --> 00:53:15,613
There's no discipline, there's no calling,

1364
00:53:15,655 --> 00:53:18,200
there's no orientation, there's no transformation.

1365
00:53:18,480 --> 00:53:19,320
Pick something.

1366
00:53:20,020 --> 00:53:23,840
If you do nothing, first of all, you can't.

1367
00:53:24,680 --> 00:53:25,560
Let's just try it.

1368
00:53:26,080 --> 00:53:27,175
You can't do nothing.

1369
00:53:27,200 --> 00:53:28,499
You're going to think,

1370
00:53:28,600 --> 00:53:31,680
you're going to fantasize, maybe bitterly.

1371
00:53:31,840 --> 00:53:33,720
There's literally no doing nothing.

1372
00:53:34,640 --> 00:53:36,700
All you're doing when you're doing nothing

1373
00:53:36,960 --> 00:53:39,665
is allowing yourself to fall under the sway

1374
00:53:40,666 --> 00:53:42,895
of the most narrow and bitter visions

1375
00:53:42,920 --> 00:53:44,480
that can possibly inhabit you.

1376
00:53:45,221 --> 00:53:46,681
Yeah, well, that's a really

1377
00:53:46,722 --> 00:53:48,349
stupid strategy, obviously.

1378
00:53:48,382 --> 00:53:50,120
So, pick something.

1379
00:53:50,280 --> 00:53:51,960
What we'll see tomorrow—here's

1380
00:53:52,360 --> 00:53:53,615
a practical solution.

1381
00:53:53,640 --> 00:53:55,063
OK, you don't know what to do.

1382
00:53:55,104 --> 00:53:58,280
Well, what do people do, broadly speaking?

1383
00:53:58,880 --> 00:54:01,026
It's like, do you have a relationship?

1384
00:54:01,280 --> 00:54:01,935
Well, no.

1385
00:54:01,960 --> 00:54:04,615
OK, well, most people want one.

1386
00:54:04,640 --> 00:54:05,695
You probably do, too.

1387
00:54:05,720 --> 00:54:07,815
So even if you don't know you

1388
00:54:07,840 --> 00:54:09,760
want one, we could try that.

1389
00:54:09,785 --> 00:54:10,960
Do you have any friends?

1390
00:54:10,985 --> 00:54:12,281
Do you have any family?

1391
00:54:12,865 --> 00:54:15,120
Are you pursuing anything educational?

1392
00:54:16,000 --> 00:54:17,600
Do you have any job?

1393
00:54:17,665 --> 00:54:19,208
Is there any way you're making

1394
00:54:19,249 --> 00:54:20,709
yourself useful to other people?

1395
00:54:20,751 --> 00:54:24,337
Do you have any interests at all outside of work?

1396
00:54:25,000 --> 00:54:25,575
Et cetera.

1397
00:54:25,600 --> 00:54:27,298
We'll go through this in detail.

1398
00:54:27,339 --> 00:54:29,174
And if you don't know what to do, it's like,

1399
00:54:29,216 --> 00:54:33,015
well, try part of one of those things and see.

1400
00:54:33,040 --> 00:54:34,975
Maybe you're one of those people

1401
00:54:35,000 --> 00:54:36,681
who just doesn't need anyone else.

1402
00:54:36,800 --> 00:54:38,295
You're not, because no one is,

1403
00:54:38,320 --> 00:54:39,680
but maybe you think that.

1404
00:54:39,960 --> 00:54:42,840
We could at least put it to the test and see.

1405
00:54:43,360 --> 00:54:45,975
Probably you want a friend, and maybe you're

1406
00:54:46,000 --> 00:54:50,280
introverted, so you want one friend, but not zero.

1407
00:54:51,440 --> 00:54:54,080
And so, if you don't know what to do,

1408
00:54:55,000 --> 00:54:56,760
nothing is the wrong solution.

1409
00:54:57,600 --> 00:54:59,415
And you can look and see what

1410
00:54:59,440 --> 00:55:01,326
other people do and try to do that.

1411
00:55:01,368 --> 00:55:03,655
And that's partly why, by the way, when you're

1412
00:55:03,680 --> 00:55:06,560
a teenager, it matters to you so much to fit in.

1413
00:55:07,040 --> 00:55:09,588
It's not like you're fitting in.

1414
00:55:10,297 --> 00:55:12,480
That's such an insane way—you know, "If

1415
00:55:13,000 --> 00:55:14,760
your friends jumped over a cliff,

1416
00:55:14,796 --> 00:55:16,005
would you jump off, too?"

1417
00:55:16,047 --> 00:55:17,256
It's like, well, probably.

1418
00:55:17,298 --> 00:55:19,575
Maybe it means there's a bear chasing us.

1419
00:55:19,600 --> 00:55:20,467
You never know.

1420
00:55:20,509 --> 00:55:21,635
It's like, of course,

1421
00:55:21,676 --> 00:55:23,303
teenagers try to fit in because they're

1422
00:55:23,344 --> 00:55:25,763
trying to socialize themselves into the group.

1423
00:55:25,805 --> 00:55:27,723
They're trying to escape from their parents

1424
00:55:27,765 --> 00:55:29,495
and their dependency, and they do

1425
00:55:29,520 --> 00:55:31,440
that by making a group affiliation.

1426
00:55:31,800 --> 00:55:34,400
Now, you can tell your kids, "Don't sell your

1427
00:55:34,446 --> 00:55:36,823
soul so that you're a member of the group."

1428
00:55:36,907 --> 00:55:39,360
That's a whole different discussion because

1429
00:55:39,880 --> 00:55:42,902
you don't want to pretend that you're

1430
00:55:42,944 --> 00:55:44,240
something that you're not.

1431
00:55:44,265 --> 00:55:46,375
You don't want to sacrifice the possibility

1432
00:55:46,400 --> 00:55:49,135
of your higher-order being to idiot

1433
00:55:49,160 --> 00:55:51,760
identification with the whim of the crowd.

1434
00:55:52,160 --> 00:55:54,615
But that's not the same thing as, "It shouldn't

1435
00:55:54,662 --> 00:55:56,664
matter to you what your friends think."

1436
00:55:56,706 --> 00:55:58,345
You know what sort of person it

1437
00:55:58,929 --> 00:56:02,480
doesn't matter to what other people think?

1438
00:56:02,720 --> 00:56:03,880
That's a psychopath.

1439
00:56:04,337 --> 00:56:06,520
And most of the time, you should be damn

1440
00:56:06,545 --> 00:56:08,540
concerned with what other people think.

1441
00:56:08,800 --> 00:56:11,920
Not always, and that's a tight discrimination.

1442
00:56:12,093 --> 00:56:14,735
But most of the time, if most people think there's

1443
00:56:14,760 --> 00:56:17,160
something wrong with you, they're probably right.

1444
00:56:17,681 --> 00:56:19,349
Sometimes they're not.

1445
00:56:19,720 --> 00:56:21,240
And that's an edge case.

1446
00:56:22,360 --> 00:56:23,180
All right.

1447
00:56:25,880 --> 00:56:27,606
Another way of looking at emotions.

1448
00:56:27,648 --> 00:56:30,680
You move from the present to the future.

1449
00:56:30,942 --> 00:56:32,695
There are things that you predict

1450
00:56:32,720 --> 00:56:34,612
that are going the way you want them to.

1451
00:56:34,654 --> 00:56:36,655
That fills you with positive emotion.

1452
00:56:36,680 --> 00:56:39,615
And then there's a category of obstacle—we'll talk

1453
00:56:39,640 --> 00:56:41,326
about this tomorrow—there's a category

1454
00:56:41,368 --> 00:56:43,078
of obstacle that's unpredictable.

1455
00:56:43,360 --> 00:56:45,815
Sometimes you'll run into obstacles that you know

1456
00:56:45,840 --> 00:56:46,440
how to move,

1457
00:56:46,840 --> 00:56:49,249
and sometimes you'll run into obstacles

1458
00:56:49,600 --> 00:56:51,720
whose nature you don't understand

1459
00:56:52,120 --> 00:56:53,292
and you can't predict.

1460
00:56:53,317 --> 00:56:54,879
You run into something you don't

1461
00:56:54,921 --> 00:56:56,975
understand about your husband, for example.

1462
00:56:57,000 --> 00:56:58,841
It's a bottomless mystery,

1463
00:56:58,880 --> 00:57:01,176
and we'll talk about that a little bit tomorrow.

1464
00:57:01,218 --> 00:57:03,320
So, three categories of

1465
00:57:04,480 --> 00:57:06,440
stimuli that you respond to emotionally.

1466
00:57:07,360 --> 00:57:09,140
Things that get you on your way,

1467
00:57:10,360 --> 00:57:12,102
things that get in your way,

1468
00:57:12,480 --> 00:57:14,520
and things you don't understand.

1469
00:57:14,560 --> 00:57:16,520
And the things you don't understand,

1470
00:57:16,920 --> 00:57:18,320
that's a bottomless pit.

1471
00:57:18,720 --> 00:57:19,440
That's a hole.

1472
00:57:19,800 --> 00:57:21,500
We'll talk about that tomorrow.

1473
00:57:27,184 --> 00:57:30,120
OK, I'll close with this one today.

1474
00:57:31,576 --> 00:57:32,800
I showed you one of these

1475
00:57:32,825 --> 00:57:34,380
little story frames, right?

1476
00:57:34,746 --> 00:57:35,413
You're here.

1477
00:57:35,455 --> 00:57:36,880
That's the present.

1478
00:57:37,240 --> 00:57:38,945
You're aiming at something.

1479
00:57:39,029 --> 00:57:40,775
The world orients itself so

1480
00:57:40,800 --> 00:57:42,836
that there are pathways forward to that.

1481
00:57:43,400 --> 00:57:46,200
You want the pathway because otherwise your

1482
00:57:47,200 --> 00:57:49,440
plan is invalidated or you'll be upset.

1483
00:57:49,760 --> 00:57:51,415
You don't want too many obstacles.

1484
00:57:51,440 --> 00:57:53,678
You want things to help you along your way.

1485
00:57:53,720 --> 00:57:54,512
That's the world.

1486
00:57:54,554 --> 00:57:56,514
You're always in a little frame like that.

1487
00:57:56,555 --> 00:57:57,840
OK, those frames are nested,

1488
00:57:58,520 --> 00:58:00,455
and that nesting is your identity.

1489
00:58:00,480 --> 00:58:02,352
When you're developing a vision,

1490
00:58:02,880 --> 00:58:05,771
you're developing the entire nested structure.

1491
00:58:06,160 --> 00:58:07,760
OK, so I'll show you how that works.

1492
00:58:08,360 --> 00:58:10,495
OK, your identity is not something

1493
00:58:10,520 --> 00:58:12,277
you carry around in your head.

1494
00:58:12,611 --> 00:58:15,215
OK, so now you're two and you have all these

1495
00:58:15,240 --> 00:58:17,280
motivational forces working within you.

1496
00:58:18,080 --> 00:58:20,534
OK, as you mature, you integrate them,

1497
00:58:20,560 --> 00:58:23,036
and you integrate them in a way that makes you

1498
00:58:23,080 --> 00:58:24,840
a good player within the family

1499
00:58:24,871 --> 00:58:26,260
and then within your friends.

1500
00:58:26,285 --> 00:58:28,960
So you integrate those instincts

1501
00:58:29,720 --> 00:58:31,600
in an increasingly social environment.

1502
00:58:32,082 --> 00:58:33,880
And then as you mature more, you

1503
00:58:34,960 --> 00:58:36,720
get better and better at doing that,

1504
00:58:37,200 --> 00:58:40,495
across longer and longer spans of time, in more

1505
00:58:40,520 --> 00:58:42,844
and more situations with more and more people.

1506
00:58:42,880 --> 00:58:44,400
OK, so let's break that down.

1507
00:58:44,800 --> 00:58:47,680
This will show you how you move from the abstract

1508
00:58:47,840 --> 00:58:49,560
moral imperative to the particular.

1509
00:58:50,240 --> 00:58:55,120
So let's say you tell your child to make dinner,

1510
00:58:56,606 --> 00:58:57,680
and he's three.

1511
00:58:58,840 --> 00:59:00,000
So he looks at you.

1512
00:59:01,276 --> 00:59:02,277
"What do you mean?"

1513
00:59:02,319 --> 00:59:04,015
And you give him a cuff because

1514
00:59:04,040 --> 00:59:05,613
he's too stupid to make dinner.

1515
00:59:05,655 --> 00:59:07,240
This is not a good plan.

1516
00:59:07,281 --> 00:59:08,680
And so what's your problem?

1517
00:59:08,705 --> 00:59:10,600
The problem is he's three.

1518
00:59:10,625 --> 00:59:12,040
OK, so why is that a problem?

1519
00:59:12,077 --> 00:59:13,735
And the problem is he doesn't know

1520
00:59:13,760 --> 00:59:15,800
what complete, make dinner means.

1521
00:59:16,680 --> 00:59:18,415
He doesn't know the micro steps.

1522
00:59:18,440 --> 00:59:20,756
When you say to someone, "Make dinner,"

1523
00:59:21,760 --> 00:59:24,640
you're assuming that they know how to make dinner.

1524
00:59:24,671 --> 00:59:26,720
You're assuming that they've been socialized

1525
00:59:26,745 --> 00:59:29,495
the same way you have been, so that when you

1526
00:59:29,520 --> 00:59:32,093
utter that phrase, they understand what it means.

1527
00:59:32,120 --> 00:59:33,375
OK, so we decompose that.

1528
00:59:33,400 --> 00:59:35,054
What does it mean to make dinner?

1529
00:59:35,096 --> 00:59:37,335
So my son's 15 months old,

1530
00:59:37,360 --> 00:59:39,815
and he's starting to learn to set the table.

1531
00:59:39,840 --> 00:59:42,240
But you can't say "set the table,"

1532
00:59:42,769 --> 00:59:44,980
partly because he can't even see the table.

1533
00:59:45,005 --> 00:59:46,560
It's here and he's this high.

1534
00:59:46,800 --> 00:59:47,760
But you can say,

1535
00:59:49,483 --> 00:59:51,276
"Do you know where the knife drawer is?"

1536
00:59:51,318 --> 00:59:52,485
He'll go, "Yes."

1537
00:59:52,527 --> 00:59:54,570
Say, "Go to the knife drawer."

1538
00:59:54,612 --> 00:59:56,335
He goes to the knife drawer.

1539
00:59:56,360 --> 00:59:57,751
"Pull the knife drawer open.

1540
00:59:58,120 --> 01:00:00,284
Feel around till you feel a knife."

1541
01:00:00,575 --> 01:00:01,295
He'll do that.

1542
01:00:01,320 --> 01:00:02,340
You can give him a pat on the head.

1543
01:00:02,365 --> 01:00:03,078
"Good work.

1544
01:00:03,495 --> 01:00:04,240
Got the knife?"

1545
01:00:04,265 --> 01:00:05,204
"Yes."

1546
01:00:05,496 --> 01:00:07,375
"Take the knife into the table

1547
01:00:07,400 --> 01:00:10,542
and put it on the top of the table."

1548
01:00:10,584 --> 01:00:12,168
OK, so what has he done?

1549
01:00:12,560 --> 01:00:14,045
He's started to set the table.

1550
01:00:14,080 --> 01:00:15,880
You see, you've broken it down, right?

1551
01:00:15,922 --> 01:00:17,006
And you've broken it down

1552
01:00:17,048 --> 01:00:18,695
to implementable subroutines.

1553
01:00:18,720 --> 01:00:22,120
So, setting the table is an integrated story.

1554
01:00:22,640 --> 01:00:24,012
It's part of an identity.

1555
01:00:24,040 --> 01:00:26,360
It's an integrated story that involves

1556
01:00:26,720 --> 01:00:28,800
a variety of mastered subroutines.

1557
01:00:28,849 --> 01:00:30,767
Part of what you're doing when you're learning

1558
01:00:30,809 --> 01:00:33,119
a new task is you have to break the task down

1559
01:00:33,960 --> 01:00:35,295
to the level of subroutine

1560
01:00:35,320 --> 01:00:37,895
that you need to master.

1561
01:00:37,920 --> 01:00:39,942
Right, and so when you're training someone,

1562
01:00:39,983 --> 01:00:41,693
the first thing you have to find out is,

1563
01:00:41,735 --> 01:00:43,063
well, what don't they know?

1564
01:00:43,088 --> 01:00:43,920
Maybe you're training

1565
01:00:43,945 --> 01:00:45,488
someone for customer service.

1566
01:00:45,520 --> 01:00:48,720
It's like, maybe they whisper on the phone.

1567
01:00:48,991 --> 01:00:50,460
You might want to find that out.

1568
01:00:50,485 --> 01:00:52,827
Do you know how to talk?

1569
01:00:53,160 --> 01:00:54,535
You might assume yes,

1570
01:00:54,560 --> 01:00:56,664
and that assumption might be completely wrong.

1571
01:00:56,706 --> 01:00:57,790
Maybe they have to triple

1572
01:00:57,832 --> 01:00:59,166
the volume of their voice.

1573
01:00:59,200 --> 01:01:02,175
You have to play until you find out at what

1574
01:01:02,200 --> 01:01:04,415
level of the subroutines the person is lacking.

1575
01:01:04,440 --> 01:01:05,588
That includes you, and you

1576
01:01:05,630 --> 01:01:07,131
build it from the bottom up.

1577
01:01:07,280 --> 01:01:12,302
So it's cut vegetables, set table, do dishes.

1578
01:01:12,344 --> 01:01:14,178
OK, that's part of completing a meal.

1579
01:01:14,220 --> 01:01:16,472
Now, if you're a halfway civilized five-year-old,

1580
01:01:16,514 --> 01:01:18,098
maybe you can make a basic meal.

1581
01:01:18,440 --> 01:01:20,615
So then you can say to your five-year-old,

1582
01:01:20,640 --> 01:01:22,602
"You know how to make some Kraft dinner?"

1583
01:01:22,644 --> 01:01:23,686
And they've got that.

1584
01:01:23,728 --> 01:01:24,979
They know where the pots are,

1585
01:01:25,021 --> 01:01:26,230
they know how to boil water.

1586
01:01:26,272 --> 01:01:28,982
So you can now tag that whole complex

1587
01:01:29,240 --> 01:01:31,415
small subpersonality with a single

1588
01:01:31,440 --> 01:01:33,096
verbal tag, and they can do it.

1589
01:01:33,403 --> 01:01:36,197
OK, so maybe if you're a good father,

1590
01:01:36,239 --> 01:01:37,323
you know how to make a meal,

1591
01:01:37,364 --> 01:01:38,657
you know how to play with the baby.

1592
01:01:38,699 --> 01:01:40,284
And what do you do when you play with the baby?

1593
01:01:40,325 --> 01:01:41,410
Well, you play peekaboo,

1594
01:01:41,451 --> 01:01:43,203
you tickle the baby, you clean the baby.

1595
01:01:43,240 --> 01:01:44,329
Those are subroutines.

1596
01:01:44,370 --> 01:01:46,038
Now you know how to take care of the baby,

1597
01:01:46,080 --> 01:01:47,331
and you know how to make a meal.

1598
01:01:47,373 --> 01:01:50,167
And so maybe that's part of being a good parent.

1599
01:01:50,640 --> 01:01:53,211
And that's part of what makes you a good partner.

1600
01:01:53,253 --> 01:01:55,505
And that's part of what makes you a good person.

1601
01:01:55,546 --> 01:01:57,965
And you can say to your wife, "Be a good person."

1602
01:01:58,246 --> 01:02:00,217
It's like, maybe you tell

1603
01:02:00,259 --> 01:02:01,468
your kids that, "Be good."

1604
01:02:01,510 --> 01:02:03,761
And sometimes they sort of know what you mean,

1605
01:02:03,793 --> 01:02:06,695
but you probably have to decompose that down

1606
01:02:06,720 --> 01:02:09,095
the hierarchy of identity till you hit the level

1607
01:02:09,120 --> 01:02:12,040
at which they're insufficient and repair that.

1608
01:02:13,280 --> 01:02:15,000
Imagine you're playing the piano,

1609
01:02:16,040 --> 01:02:18,135
playing a complex melody, and you trip

1610
01:02:18,160 --> 01:02:21,175
over a note, and you do that repeatedly.

1611
01:02:21,200 --> 01:02:22,819
So what you do is, you slow down,

1612
01:02:22,861 --> 01:02:25,029
and then you concentrate on the place where you

1613
01:02:25,071 --> 01:02:27,406
made a mistake, and then you see what you're doing

1614
01:02:27,448 --> 01:02:28,695
when you make the mistake,

1615
01:02:28,720 --> 01:02:30,409
and then you adjust that,

1616
01:02:30,450 --> 01:02:32,960
and then you practice the adjustment till you've

1617
01:02:32,985 --> 01:02:35,640
automated it, then you integrate it in the rhythm,

1618
01:02:35,880 --> 01:02:37,440
then you play the whole phrase,

1619
01:02:37,465 --> 01:02:38,695
and then you go over it.

1620
01:02:38,720 --> 01:02:40,459
That's exactly what you do when you're

1621
01:02:40,500 --> 01:02:42,669
trying to solve a problem of adaptation.

1622
01:02:42,720 --> 01:02:43,920
You hit an obstacle,

1623
01:02:44,400 --> 01:02:46,175
you decompose it down the hierarchy

1624
01:02:46,200 --> 01:02:49,880
of specialization till you see where the error is,

1625
01:02:50,640 --> 01:02:53,055
the minimal error, rectify that, practice

1626
01:02:53,080 --> 01:02:55,440
the rectification, and then sequence back up.

1627
01:02:56,120 --> 01:02:58,135
And then you're aiming always up.

1628
01:02:58,160 --> 01:03:01,215
When you're training your two-year-old to put

1629
01:03:01,240 --> 01:03:03,040
a butter knife on the table,

1630
01:03:03,520 --> 01:03:06,560
it's a subset of helping him become a good person.

1631
01:03:07,680 --> 01:03:10,520
But that good person isn't some

1632
01:03:11,480 --> 01:03:13,440
disembodied abstraction.

1633
01:03:13,989 --> 01:03:18,800
It's the integrated hierarchy of a set of leveled

1634
01:03:18,960 --> 01:03:21,720
specializations all aiming in the same direction.

1635
01:03:22,640 --> 01:03:23,895
I'll close with this.

1636
01:03:23,920 --> 01:03:26,495
Here's a way of conceptualizing that.

1637
01:03:26,520 --> 01:03:29,575
Let's say you have a highly skilled athlete

1638
01:03:29,600 --> 01:03:34,009
on your team who's also elected by

1639
01:03:35,677 --> 01:03:37,720
his peers to be the captain of the team

1640
01:03:38,280 --> 01:03:40,220
because of his leadership abilities.

1641
01:03:40,680 --> 01:03:42,375
OK, so then you can imagine

1642
01:03:42,400 --> 01:03:44,320
what athlete means in that context.

1643
01:03:44,400 --> 01:03:47,000
It means, let's say, possibly,

1644
01:03:47,240 --> 01:03:49,360
he's the most skilled player on the team.

1645
01:03:50,017 --> 01:03:51,615
But what do you mean skilled?

1646
01:03:51,640 --> 01:03:53,728
Well, maybe he can score the most goals,

1647
01:03:53,760 --> 01:03:55,460
but that's not sufficient, right?

1648
01:03:56,240 --> 01:03:58,495
He needs to score the most goals in a way

1649
01:03:58,520 --> 01:04:00,480
that motivates everyone else on the team

1650
01:04:00,920 --> 01:04:04,095
to score the most goals themselves and to improve

1651
01:04:04,120 --> 01:04:07,895
in their capacity to do that over time and not

1652
01:04:07,920 --> 01:04:10,720
to be jealous of the differences in skill

1653
01:04:10,837 --> 01:04:13,615
at the team level and to get along in a way

1654
01:04:13,640 --> 01:04:15,204
that makes the entire enterprise

1655
01:04:15,246 --> 01:04:17,957
worth replicating over and over.

1656
01:04:18,207 --> 01:04:19,855
And so if you do that, well,

1657
01:04:19,880 --> 01:04:21,460
then you're a skilled athlete.

1658
01:04:21,501 --> 01:04:26,135
And that's the same in the broader moral domain,

1659
01:04:26,160 --> 01:04:27,423
is you want to be skilled

1660
01:04:27,465 --> 01:04:29,550
at the specific things that you do.

1661
01:04:29,675 --> 01:04:32,052
You want to have the perceptions and the actions

1662
01:04:32,093 --> 01:04:34,080
at hand that enable you to do that.

1663
01:04:34,105 --> 01:04:36,040
But you want to have them integrated

1664
01:04:36,065 --> 01:04:39,015
into a personality that makes all of the games

1665
01:04:39,040 --> 01:04:41,309
that you're playing work in a broader game

1666
01:04:41,351 --> 01:04:44,079
and work repetitively with other

1667
01:04:44,440 --> 01:04:46,320
people in a self-improving direction.

1668
01:04:47,880 --> 01:04:50,480
If you do that, your life will be meaningful,

1669
01:04:51,800 --> 01:04:53,320
because meaning is the instinct

1670
01:04:54,040 --> 01:04:57,073
that tells you that you're doing that.

1671
01:04:57,114 --> 01:04:59,116
It's not some metaphysical abstraction that you

1672
01:04:59,160 --> 01:05:00,409
can eradicate with, like,

1673
01:05:00,450 --> 01:05:01,735
a nihilistic rationalism.

1674
01:05:01,760 --> 01:05:03,078
"What's the point of life?"

1675
01:05:03,119 --> 01:05:05,705
It's an experiential reality.

1676
01:05:06,200 --> 01:05:09,295
It means that you're existing in harmony with your

1677
01:05:09,320 --> 01:05:11,585
integration towards the highest possible purpose.

1678
01:05:11,626 --> 01:05:13,169
That's a good way of thinking about.

1679
01:05:13,211 --> 01:05:14,879
Your conscience will aid you in that,

1680
01:05:14,921 --> 01:05:17,673
and so will the manifestation of your interests.

1681
01:05:17,715 --> 01:05:19,855
OK, tomorrow, we'll talk about how to make

1682
01:05:19,880 --> 01:05:21,975
that concrete, to bring it all the way

1683
01:05:22,000 --> 01:05:23,928
down to Earth, because you can do that.

1684
01:05:23,970 --> 01:05:25,263
You can and you need to.

1685
01:05:25,346 --> 01:05:26,280
All right.

1686
01:05:26,640 --> 01:05:27,723
Thank you very much.